Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko 
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, in the framework of an amendment to the criminal law, the annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition. 
MEPs refused in second reading the proposed amendment aimed at reducing penalties for economic crimes, which could open the doors of freedom for the former First Minister currently imprisoned. 
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having reached an agreement, a priori disadvantage with Russia for the purchase of natural gas. 
The judgment is not final, and the court must rule on the appeal of the sentenced in December. 
Tymosenko describes the political judgment of revenge of the regime and has caused suspicions of partiality of the court in the west. 
The project to cancel paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Premère Minister has been condemned, has been signed by 147 Members. 
It would have required 226 votes to approve it. 
