IBM's history: from slices of cheese to flights in the cosmos. 
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a century ago; it was originally the complicated name of Tabulating Computing Corporation. 
She took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America. 
The basis of the future IBM has been the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80 year nineteenth. 
They had technologies such as the old "pointeuses," which recorded the arrival and departure of employees. 
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the Council of Surveillance of society. 
Flint hired the head of a rival firm Thomas J. Watson to help lead the company. 
The leader then presented the shadows to the founder of the firm - it is on the ideas of Watson that are so far the identity and culture of society. 
Watson led the firm kusqu' in 1952. 
IBM, as its name, began with the production of all possible machines for business and trade - seed cutters of cheese and meat until the cash registers. 
During the first four years in which Watson led, the turnover was multiplied up to $9 million and began the expansion of the firm in all parts of the world. 
Watson was the firm so irreplaceable that after 40 years of leadership is his son who served as the director, Thomas J Watson. 
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language. 
In the 1960s people and computers of IBM helped NASA guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the moon. 
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360. 
The classic PC that determined the standard computer with the IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981. 
Twenty years later IBM sells its computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with advice and services with a high added value. 
The strategy that succeeds in IBM over the past three years - is the concept Smarter Planet "a smarter planet." 
Its goal is the uilisation smart technology in untapped areas such as transportation and management of cities. 
In terms of trade IBM has developed a platform "Smarter Trade" that helps business manage the business cycle. 
IBM has a strong history on our territory. 
It set up its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe. 
Today, in addition to IBM, there is also the strategic centre since Brno. 
The Central for the Central and Eastern Europe headquarters in Prague, and there is also the team of research and development of the global recognition of the floor. 
