How have changed the price of travel since 1989 
Until 1989 there were in Czechoslovakia only five travel agencies: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist. 
Travel agencies at the time of travel, especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the West were very limited. 
The Czech tourists were travelling for the holiday in Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), in Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton). 
A big exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel in Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a penchant for the West and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists. 
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it nétait not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechs) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries. 
In cases where the Tchécoslovaque citizen wanted to travel individually for example in Poland and the Soviet Union had a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed. 
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West must also be queuing all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency. 
And even after that it was not yet won. 
The agreement for the currency was the condition for travel to the West was denied the "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all. 
The Czechoslovak currency was not, however, shared and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the consent of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west. 
The Czechs were the more frequently their holidays in the country where there were so many campaign houses and cottages that the Czechs are bought and usually lasts until now. 
The journeys of the Czechs have since seen since 1989 a major revolution. 
Although until 1989 holidays in Germany and Bulgaria were at most, the Czechs have spent the last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world. 
The great paradox that we did not realise today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to move freely until 1989 as part of Yugoslavia at the time. 
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the west have caused a huge wave of visits short mainly in Austria in Vienna and Germany. 
The Czechs could not long fly to the West that everyone wanted to see at least a moment. 
For example, in Paris the travel organisations were sleeping the Czechs in tents in parks because our income could not pay the hotel or a pension. 
The typical feature of a trip of Czechs was at this time to take away its own canned food, sausage, etc... to save. 
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown that has enabled our tourists finally after dozens of years to be able to freely buy the Western currency. 
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased what has caused around the year 1997 another important moment. 
Thanks to a growing demand for travel travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare towers with charter air links through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what there was before. 
In the late 1990s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world who later facilitated our trips. 
Another interesting moment in the history of tourism after the revolution, when prepared the first charter flight to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic. 
Since this year as every year Air Carriers' direct visit Czech tourists in distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic. 
It is more than 100,000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year! 
An interesting moment in this period that symbolises our revolution happened in 2008. 
On 17 November 2008 the EU have abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to move completely in the group of developed countries. 
In 2008 the Czechs for the first time in history have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history have spent more than 15,000 kronor per person for holidays abroad including incidentals kronor per person. 
The General Assembly must find its President, but this is likely to be completed by an unresolved situation "by" 
5mois already Czech football is without President and the risk that the successor of Ivan Hasek at the head of the Football Association of the Czech Republic is not yet known after a General Assembly scheduled Thursday at Nymburk. 
However, there is still no agreement on how to vote. 
Without this agreement, it is not possible to begin to vote for one of the three candidates. 
Rajchl Jindrich, Miroslav Pelta and Tomas Paclik are interested in the direction of the Czech football. 
Hasek resigned in June and his departure has called on his colleagues to come together and find a strong personality who will lead the football in the future. 
Only during the era after Hasek football is back to differences between the chambers of the Association who cannot agree on a common candidate. 
This has fully demonstrated on 16 September when he had to choose a new president. 
The delegates of the General Assembly met unnecessarily in the national House in Prague because the negotiations are blocked and it has not even been discussed to address how to elect. 
There is no agreement on who has the right to vote in the General Assembly - only, it seems, the statutory representatives, or officials with full powers. 
In this single point there has been a partial agreement since this moment with the assistance of the Office for the state and the law, according to which the representation on the basis of full power is not possible. 
The differences still persist about the rules for the election. 
It is all too clear that the executive committee, which in its extraordinary or planned negotiations, has brought nothing to the situation 
Views on the voting possibilit? have changed several times, but the key point remains the same. 
The question is: how to proceed in the third round in order not to fall into the by. 
"The bone of contention is the following: either proceed according to the statutes or find another model," noted one of the three vice-presidents of the Football Association of the Czech Republic Dusan Svoboda representing professional football within the association. 
According to the rules of the model predicted gains in the third round of the candidates who have received the most votes in proportion to the chamber for which he is a candidate. 
Moravia is ready to withdraw so that wins the candidate who receives the largest percentage of votes of the two chambers. 
The Czech side is studying the condition that the winner should have at least two thirds of the percentages of votes. 
"Only this would then lose the idea of two previous rounds, and it would completely reject the bicameral concept," admits Svoboda who understands the objections of the Moravian party and who would be better not to change the regulation and vote according to the statutes in force. 
It is surprising that Tomas Paclik also agree, even if he believes that the settlement of elections established under the statute Pelta advantage among all candidates. 
"I hope that we vote at the maximum, according to the statutes of the association." 
"So that there is not yet insane ideas dreamt up by a representative during the past General Assemblies," said the owner of Victoria Plzen candidate for the first time and in its submissions was defined primarily against Pelta. 
Pelta remains optimistic. 
He said Nymburk there will be a new President and believes that the candidates will cooperate in the future together and constructively. 
"The qualification possible today in European Championships should calm everybody." 
"Football will again on a wave of happiness and there is one more way for cooperation," added the Jablonec officer who among the three was the greatest experience in professional football at the regional level. 
Rajchl is more pessimistic. 
"I believe in this agreement, but unfortunately the situation is very tense." 
"This is not a problem between the Czechs and the Moravians, but there are trends to change the regulations to design." 
"This can cause a blockage in the General Assembly." 
"I hope that good reason will win," said Rajchl. 
There is not much time for a common agreement to all parties. 
Some réuunions should be held directly in Montenegro, but who can say whether the direction of football will be complete for the game. 
The special charter flight which had to travel up to Podgorice including the Vice-Presidents Kucera and Rajchl Dalibor, did not take off for technical reasons and sought a variant to take part of the Executive Committee on the ground of retaliation. 
At the end is the ministerial meeting, which could take place on Wednesday, which should be decisive. 
The Minister of Education for Youth and Sports Joseph Dobes would be very happy to receive the parties within the sports association the highest in the country and bring them to an agreement. 
In the game there are many: a state allocation, the credibility of football and the General Assembly of the Czech Union Sports, which must determine the direction of Czech sport after the financial problems of Sazka. 
