Europe's finest swimming pools 
A leap in the blue 
Julia Stanek 
Wading pools of UFO, beautiful swimming pools in Budapest: who travels across Europe can live his blue miracle - and turned the city or a long walk - can leave her tired legs in soft-drink baths. 
A book shows in which swimming pool can experience the most well-being. 
When Iris Meder went into research trip during the last 18 months, there is an object that should not miss in his baggage: his swimsuit. 
Lying on his back in the water, she retorted cupolas artistically arranged, and swimming against the marbles Putten expected from the other side of the pool and failed to admire Art Nouveau meticulously restored these converted swimming pools. 
If a covered swimming pool was fun, she noted in her book without delay all the details of interest on the type of construction and the history of the building. 
More than 200 pools were surveyed in this way by the architectural historian Meder and presented in his book already published: "Badefreuden (Joies Bain." municipal swimming pools covered in Munich, the historic palace bloodbath in the woods, "concrete buildings Hardcore" in the Taunus. 
She has led her "trips to the most outstanding baths of Central Europe" in 13 countries: Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia. 
The German 46 years is a true devotee of the culture of the bath. 
Meder, explains that it is not a great deal of interest in sport but Yukon feels attracted to water in a completely different way. 
It is irritating that swimming fans should simply look blue tiles and cope with the stench of bleach while joggers breathe perfume relatively stable populations of spruce forests or can listen to the joyous trill of birds in the park. 
"I asked myself why swimming pools must always be so ugly," said the Viennese. 
"I started a collection of beautiful baths." 
The surface of the water doubly reinforces the architecture 
A dive in a swimming pool and sauna volatile oils - factor of wellbeing in the swimming rooms are enormous because all the senses are awake, according to Meder. 
And if the builders would be given a little more room to swim could be a real delight for the eyes: "Instead of a floor surface water in the swimming rooms." 
"It is transparent, but reflects the beauty of the whole building." 
All surfaces are optically double: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards. 
The volume of image of small "Badefreuden" is a report worth 190 pages on the history of architecture and culture on the oasis of historic welfare - he certainly want to make a leap into the blue. 
The Meder collector has discovered remarkable copies during his research in Hungary. 
Alongside welfare splendid baths as the Szechenyi bath aged 100 years ago in Budapest, she found nitrate-containing in a natural cave in the Karst cave in Miskolc - Tapolca) as well as a bath baths whose basins are filled with water containing alcali (and Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény) and located in a building in the form of a bottle. 
By contrast, the outdoor heated swimming pools of Switzerland and Austria offers spectacular views. While a bath house in Zurich was the entire city in his eyes, you can admire the snowy Arlberg from an outdoor swimming pool in St Anton: the Turkish bath is equipped with a window from which we can observe animation on the ski hill. 
Perhaps the most extraordinary design of swimming pool awaits swimmers in Längenfeld: the Aqua Dome Ötztal resembles a UFO that has just landed on the Alps. 
In winter, steam rises from the three open shelves, while in the background are the mountains of the Ötztal into the sky. 
Algesiras in the Black Forest 
The smell of bleach does not come from all the swimming pools of the Meder collection. 
Many thermal baths are a smell of sulphur, Árpád spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba is a strong smell of oil, that it is hard to believe, to find themselves in a health spa. 
The smell is coming from the alkaline waters containing hydrogen carbon that is almost black and silt you stuck to the skin as soon as you let slip into the pool - a special spa experience. 
During his quest of the beautiful swimming pools, Iris Meder has also suffered disappointments: when she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor pool and outdoor of Czechoslovakia, she found herself in a barricaded area. 
The bath designed by the Du?an architèque Jurkovic in 1902 was meanwhile closed. 
A glance through the window of the building - Art Nouveau in red, white and yellow, she has observed the development of weeds between the tiles. 
She has observed an opposite effect in a charming swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Baths of Bad Wildbad. 
This building has already survived three phases; you can discover not only elements New Roman leaving since its conception in 1844 but still a Moorish Alhambra style room was added in 1900. 
Since its careful modernization of 1995, the palace spa remains the favorite bath pool expert, Iris Meder - and not only because she is a native of Schwarzwald. 
"It is already a beautiful performance that if different styles of building a formidable unit," said Meder. 
With such a palace, diving in the pool is apparently only a minor issue. 
Agricultural speculation 
The German bank examines in detail speculation on raw materials 
Christian Teevs 
The German bank abandons its speculation on raw materials? 
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, Josef Ackermann has appointed a working group to investigate the consequences of speculation for the world's poor. 
In January, the leader of the group then wants to draw the consequences. 
Hamburg 
For the citizens of the Federal Republic, the thing is clear: according to a study, 84% of Germans find it unacceptable that the banks are speculating on raw materials such as corn and wheat. 
Two thirds of respondents demand that the German bank and other credit institutions discontinuent this business avenue because it increases the problems of the poorest in the world. 
This is the result of a Forsa survey on the order of the consumer organisation Foodwatch. 
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October. 
The author Harald Schumann highlighted in this article that speculation on raw materials, pushing prices upwards and that the banks share a complicity in the global famine. 
The campaign to protect consumers aligns specifically against the head of the Deutsche Bank, Josef Ackermann, even if the big banks like Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley are acting in the same way. 
Speculation on raw materials was initially introduced to protect merchants against price fluctuations. 
But the majority of experts meanwhile share the view that the gamblers have posted offers and demand - and benefit very poor. 
Ackermann responded to the criticism of American competitors differently: he promised to investigate the accusations and said, "nothing is worth jeopardizing the good reputation of the Deutsche Bank." 
According to Spiegel Online, an international working group is currently examining the accusations of Foodwatch. 
The review must be completed by the end of the year, then the results of the board of directors of the Deutsche Bank must be presented with a recommendation, usually. 
At the end of January, the head of the Bank will indicate the consequences. 
It could be a reduction in the market for raw materials, or even a complete abandonment. 
Ackermann built its Image 
The head of Foodwatch Thilo Bode has welcomed the news, but at the same time confirmed its criticism of the financial sector: "Speculation on rising food prices shows a particularly drastic, how banks today are detrimental to the general interest." 
Ackermann is the first banking lobby to be today especially under obligation. 
"The Deutsche Bank must remove all of its portfolio investments, for which money has been spent on food speculation," said Bode. 
"It is important for Mr. Ackermann, if it is a question of starving people or whether the reputation of the Deutsche Bank is at stake." 
The awareness of Ackermann at first glance may seem surprising, but it is clear that the CEO of the group would like to present a perfect image, a few months before leaving office. 
Deutsche Bank did announce on Monday that the President of the Council of Administration will not change what is planned within the Council of Administration. 
It could improve its brand with an abandonment of the controversial agricultural speculation. 
And about possible losses, it has little to worry about - his successor will be. 
One in two would terminate investments on raw materials. 
Foodwatch strives to maintain a strong pressure on the manager. 
So far more than 30,000 Internet users have already participated in the campaign of the organization. 
Bode released the survey Tuesday, with which 7 and 8 November the Forsa Institute has conducted surveys among 1,001 people. 
Just 11 percent found it legitimate that Deutsche Bank proposes investments for which bets on the price of food products are made. 
Many of the bank's customers would also personal consequences if they were told that their bank is involved in such operations: one in two would terminate, following the survey, all investments for which money is injected into the speculation on raw materials. 
43% déconseilleraient of such a bank in their entourage, 49% said they think about the termination of their account to change banking institution. 
21st house in Vienna 
The Pavilion, which moved 
Ingeborg Wiensowski 
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, has been a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin. 
Now it is once again open and exhibition house. 
If there is enthusiasm for a modern postwar architecture, for his clear forms, its glass hangars, its bright and bold and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technological progress, then the flag of the Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for Expo in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example. 
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once the "great Architecture Prize" for its construction steel and glass, light and suspended. 
Construction is seen until today as a milestone in contemporary architecture. 
He has made so famous architects, that he has also built the Pavilion for Expo. 
With his legendary home to four cylinders of BMW and its adjacent construction bowl in Munich, he finally became famous at the international level in 1973. 
His draft flag as a temporary construction had been exposed after the World Exposition in the Garden at the railway station in the south of Vienna, has been transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened 
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to display the works of art, not a good environment. 
However, it has been so long that contemporary art gets a new building in Vienna. 
Since 2001 the building was empty and has become increasingly dilapidated. 
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "home of the 21st century" and will in future be used as a museum for contemporary art. 
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere museum opened, in which the house is the first exhibition - a stroke of luck at any point of view. 
The new start was carried out by Agnes Husslein - Arco, which became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere. 
Husslein - Arco, has promoted an art historian at a considerable career in his youth skater, subsequently at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as a founding director of the museum of modern art in Salzburg, she has led to particularly well the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments, it has received public funds and private sponsorship and exploitation. 
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation is the same name have been exposed, a cafe and a bookshop, and an office should be built. 
Strict supervision, small budget 
Krischanitz was the ideal interpreter. 
Not only because he had transformed and expanded with sensitivity the secession of Joseph Olbracht, and that he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that the flag was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "virtually every weekend" exhibitions. 
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost generosity and lightness following his trip to Vienna and his change of use. 
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "an abyss," says Krischanitz. 
The profiles of windows of glass facades were changed, glass insulation reinforced fibreglass was raised and the roof replaced by a particular safety glass. 
The beams of thermal bridges have been strengthened or replaced, and filled with asbestos have been rehabilitated. 
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a sign of subdued light between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the slight Schwanzer Pavilion. 
The outer doors of origins remained, the house is painted in a colour protection against rust red-brown color. 
And the movie theatre is even identical to what it once was. 
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget. 
"Often materials that are good and cheap were to be found, and which also appealed to the Office of the monuments," said Krischanitz, and it draws attention to a crude soil underground. 
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light. 
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which originated in Brussels," said Krischanitz recently, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City." 
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and is still "awaken the conscience." 
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Garden Switzerland is precisely the "area of Central Station" newly planned, with offices and apartments. 
And another stroke of luck might happen: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the addition of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought Berlin's temporary art centre, and as it is said, it is already negotiating with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Garden. 
