The bank scandal of Lake Zurich 
The most adventurous Bank of Europe is not in Italy or in France, but in Switzerland. 
UBS has almost collapsed in the financial crisis and in the meantime patina of a crisis. 
It is a German who must now lead. 
It is certainly not what Axel Weber was imagined. 
After his dramatic departure from the head of the Bundesbank; it was informed in July that it would be in 2013 a position almost as spectacular: President of the Council of Administration of the big Swiss bank UBS - a big step towards an unexpected and lucrative career. 
Axel Weber publicly welcomed, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its strength recently obtained and kind comments on future colleagues. 
"UBS has succeeded the Turnaround." 
"I am pleased with the collaboration with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel." 
And yet, from the month of September, it was clear that everything was going to change. 
A UBS securities dealer in London diverted all security systems of the Bank and had approximately 1.7 billion euros. 
The head of the board of directors of UBS Oswald Grübel, a well-known banker not only in Switzerland, had to leave. 
The Chairman of the board of directors of UBS is seen as suffering - and all asking: when Axel Weber is it finally? 
We have already learned that Weber can be advised of the bank from February 2012. 
And it will resume the presidency in May - not in 2013, as provided by the bank on Tuesday. 
For Axel Weber it becomes difficult. 
It is not a banker, much more Professor d " economy and President of the bank, and it would certainly have needed a period of adjustment. 
Suddenly he is assuming responsibility for the strategy of a bank, which has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of "the biggest bank scandal in Europe." 
Indeed, UBS is a huge part - until recently, it was the biggest asset manager in the world, and on the other, it patina for years of a scandal. 
Nothing, it seems, is the proud Swiss bank. 
It started during the financial crisis. 
Until 2007 UBS had an excellent reputation. 
The image of the Swiss manager of assets, silent and sound, but also clever, it had combined with ambitious goals: it wanted to also become, in the area of investment banking, a very large bank. 
UBS managed in 2007 with $1.6 billion more money from a wealthy clientele than any other bank in the world. 
On the other hand, it was advanced as a bank of investment in the league of the largest banks in the world. 
This made sense. 
The former banker Hans Geiger and later professor of bank for many years in Zurich said: "I have always taken the UBS as a model of good bank in front of my students." 
"In the current context, one wonders: how is it that I could simply be mistaken at this point?" 
It is profoundly wrong. 
In 2007 it emerged that for the first time something amiss at UBS. 
In the middle of the year President Peter Wuffli withdrew surprisingly, which was considered previously as a senior intellectual as well as a brilliant banker. 
A few months later why he was gone. 
The division of the bank had soared with sub-prime documents and a cross on billions. 
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion francs and made a cross. 
For this reason it has indeed found investors, but that little time before, would have furrowed eyebrows: a transparent bottom of Asian state from Singapore and an Arab state, which was ignored, to the point that it has never even learned his name. 
It was only the first blow. 
In April 2008 it has worsened. 
The bank was to announce losses worth billions, the chairman of the board of directors Marcel Ospel, who was still in 2006 the second highest-paid board of directors of Switzerland, withdrew. 
In October 2008 the disaster followed: UBS, given its investment errors in the financial crisis before the bankruptcy and had to be rescued by the state. 
The national bank bought UBS tens of billions of securities issues, the Swiss Confederation has given six billion francs for convertible bonds, for which she could become co-owner of the bank. 
Switzerland has been shaken - because it noted how it can be dramatic for a small country, so big banks. 
Finally, the total balance sheet of the UBS 2007 rose to more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see chart). 
"We have not been able to save UBS again," said the bank researcher, Geiger. 
After the first disaster was followed by the second. 
Already a few months before, UBS had capitulated because of a tax dispute with America and is ready to publish the data of the wealthy clientele, who had defrauded the tax authorities, perhaps with the help of the Bank. 
In addition, it has accepted a payment of 780 million dollars in repayment of unjustified profits from these operations with a fine. 
UBS has more or less published that it had helped to tax fraud. 
At the same time it has lost something that has always been its capital in competition with wealthy clients: the prestige of discretion. 
After the scandal, the Swiss banking secrecy has not been the same. 
It followed the removal of the head of the board of directors and the chairman of the board of directors. 
And the exodus of client money. 
The bank had lost its credibility in a few months in the two main business lines: investment banking because of bad speculation and the management of assets because of tax fraud. 
And, as there was somewhat a return to calm, and as we thought, that UBS would get back, he followed this unfortunate story of merchants: a single merchant is surging 1.7 billion euros, before the bank noticing that something amiss. 
And it publishes: risk management in investment bank that does not work. 
"With the Adoboli case, it was found that the risk control too little," said Martin Janssen, an economist and professor of finance at the Institute of the University of Zurich. 
The financial director of a large German bank says: "The problem of UBS is that it has no control of the risks." 
However, it was exactly the idea of prudence, with which the Swiss bankers had long since taken their function to become guardian of the great wealth of the world: not too great risks, but security for the money - and the world could well collapse beyond the Alpine republic. 
The treasures of the Swiss banks had become the symbol of an unshakeable reliability as Lindt and Sprüngli for a particularly noble chocolate. 
UBS in Zurich still goes hand in hand with the strong cliché of the Swiss private bank - it is only a little more. 
Already, the situation is classic. 
The Bank has its seat at the railway station in Zurich, which leads directly to the railway station in Lake Zurich, which itself is surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains. 
The buildings here are prestigious, retail rents are among the highest in Europe. 
Watchmakers like Tiffany's, midway between the Swiss traditions stores like those of the Sprüngli confectionery. 
For centuries the Swiss bankers have resided here: the national bank through the palace of Credit Suisse to elitist private banks like Julius Bär. 
It arrives in the entrance hall of the UBS through a heavy door. 
Inside, walls are sheathed in marble, with thick leather chairs, and alongside the logo of the bank, a major label for "safe." 
UBS knows what the client here: security. 
This idea of the Swiss bank has ruled out of the market - or betrayed the two major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the leader of a small Swiss private bank. 
He would prefer not to read his name in the newspaper, ultimately like all Swiss bankers with the two big banks. 
UBS would become far too big, especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons are also prevalent. 
The Swiss would have nothing more to say. 
"And even if they have long been adapted to the mores of the Anglo-Saxons." 
This was indeed the Anglo-Saxon investment bank that has changed the UBS, it has made high profits and then the debacle: no financial institution has lost so much money in the jungle of sub-prime as the big Swiss bank. 
The disaster became apparent on 15 October 2008. 
"This Wednesday, the coalition government of the small country of seven million inhabitants has undertaken the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," wrote the author Lukas Hässig in his book "the crash of UBS." 
With up to 68 billion francs around 45 billion euros, politicians have agreed to save the bankrupt bank. 
How this could happen? 
If you talk with Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly to the size of the UBS. 
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks have entered into a huge group. 
A bank was created, which was already too big for the small Swiss - and has been steadily increasing. 
What has helped is that the two prédécesseuses banks UBS completed: a rich bank, but lethargy with strong management of assets in Zurich and a poorer, but certainly more internationalized. 
Suddenly, the international investment banks have had access to a lot of money, with which they were able to turn a huge wheel. 
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS, Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 Head of UBS, Marcel Ospel, formerly chairman of the board of directors. 
"I always thought that Wuffli and Ospel was a dream team," said the researcher from banks, Hans Geiger. 
"Wuffli, the great intellectual modest, which are very good models and statistics, and Ospel, intuitive, which has blazed a path to the summit with the learning of the bank." 
But Ospel would face " at the end to Wuffli. 
And wuffli would probably have made a decisive mistake at the end: "He thought that his models were the reality," Geiger said. 
"This is a tragic fall." 
Tragic, perhaps. 
One thing is clear: the exuberance arrived before the fall. 
The staff of the UBS clearly remembers the leaders' meetings during which the leader of the group Wuffli has always delivered the same watchword: displace Goldman Sachs. 
The US bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world. 
It has commissioned the "League Tables" rankings, which have documented the success of the banks at this time. 
After all, UBS wanted to climb above. 
Some steps have already been successful. 
In case of currency and securities transactions it has played a very important role. 
Business advisers, who have been responsible, have pointed out, however, a weakness: in the international operations of interest in the banking jargon "fixed," there would be a huge difference compared to the largest banks. 
UBS would have shortcomings in US mortgages. 
To fill this gap, UBS has launched an adventure, which has almost cost. 
Hungry for growth, it is also the bank itself that a fund management created before it in the US sub-prime investments that have invested. 
It has turned into a massive machine that has packaged and put the documents of value based on mortgages in the US - but which has also retained risks. 
Even when other banks have long sought to get out. 
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the real estate market was in flames, the UBS bought here," says Geiger, the banking expert. 
The euphoria over the fall is brutal. 
