Smart crows spread in cities 
In many places, rooks are regarded as "oiseaux° problem" but experts say that these highly intelligent animals are no longer chasing cities for a long time. 
Some love, some others want to get rid of them as quickly as possible; crows belong to the city for centuries, but in many communities residents' complaints are increasing because of the dirt and noise of the animals. 
An antidote against the "°problème bird" is not yet in sight. 
During the first ostfriesisch symposium on crows, experts have said that this is no longer possible to hunt the rooks of cities. 
Experts from across Germany deliberated on possible solutions. 
They are looking for alternatives in cities 
The protectors of nature makes the problems of cities on the exodus of rooks particularly protected: the use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroy traditional vital spaces. 
Hunting, landscaping and tree typical eggs made life difficult for birds. 
Crows are under the protection of nature. 
There are large colonies with more than 600 pairs of eggs in the westfälischen Soest, in the northwest including Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen. 
In 2005, a controversial project had won negative ads because of the massacre of crows in this region. 
Critics have found the capture of birds in traps and their killing with cudgels particularly brutal. 
"Normal expulsion, ousting, does nothing," said city planner and landscape, Werner Klöver. 
The destruction of nests using water under pressure or trees, often produces undesirable consequences, said the expert Manfred Kaiser of Lahr in Baden-Württemberg. 
"Animals away, large colonies divide and disperse in other places." 
The drive is conceivable only in exceptional cases, such as in hospitals, retirement homes or schools. 
"We are forced to live with them, we can no longer kill them." 
The problem cannot be solved in cities without the inclusion of the periphery, according to the opinion of the mayor Wolfgang Kellner. 
Conceivable is a combination of the ousting of animals to a aversif packaging and aggressive offers to relocate. 
Psychologist and ethnologist, Uta Maria Jürgens tried "info signs chainsaws" in order to establish relations completely different: "We can finally withstand a button in the face with a dose of self-confidence." 
Jürgens co-founded the Ascheberger journey - educational baskets in Schleswig-Holstein, signs advising on the lives of these highly intelligent rooks. 
This project has now been adopted by tourists. 
Jürgen gave his own opinion about the criticism of the noise caused by the birds: "This is a lot of communication, these birds have much to say." 
The intelligence and the ability of animals are legendary: the rooks are not only working tools to reach a beauty, but they manufacture their tools as instruments of work. 
Éthologistes of the University of Cambridge tested four rooks recently, how is the intelligence of the birds. 
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to toppling scaffolding with stones to achieve a larva. 
Without much training, they recognized déterminément that a stone had to have some size and shape to sink the platform. 
In a second trial, clever crows had to solve a problem more chunky. 
In a cylinder vertically placed, researchers had placed a small bucket with a larva. 
The birds could not reach their spoils with their beaks. 
However, the researchers had put pieces of wire at their disposal. 
All four animals were a hook with which they fished the small bucket of the small pipe. 
Three of the four rooks are even from the beginning. 
