The mass slaughter 
The new book by Peter Englund offers depth and generosity. "The Beauty and the Sorrow: Intimate History of the First World War (" beauty and grief: an intimate history of the First World War), it begins with a long list of characters that give you the heart. 
A council to start: carefully tear up this page and make your mark - page. 
You will learn to know these people in great detail. In this narrative fiction of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be disturbed and desperate in the fog of war. 
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist. 
It is also the new Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for literature. 
He wrote a book outside that he described, accurately, as "a book of history." 
It includes a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion on strategies and equipment. 
This is not so much a book about what happened, he says, that a "book describing how this might look like." " feelings, impressions, experiences and moods. " 
"The beauty and sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, young schoolgirls and botanists there, doctors, paramedics and sellers. 
Some will become heroes. 
Other prisoners of war, some will lose members, will become crazy or lose their lives. 
Their lives reeling here as the candles of a church: while some are suppressed, revival. 
The book by Peter Englund departs from the traditional history books. 
It brings a denial to the idea that the First World War is that the terrible war trenches on the Western Front. 
"The beauty and sorrow" skillfully described other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa. 
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem. 
This book is moving from the first page. 
The war took the lives of these people as a natural disaster such as Hurricane Katrina pue the cordite explosive. 
When gun shots are heard in the distance, and that you are a mother at home, are you or evade you? 
Who will come anyway? 
Almost nobody can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war. 
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been amplified by assumptions, expectations, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors." 
"The beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the fleet of high seas. 
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published. 
The versions of their lives can be terrifying and exciting, but are more preserved thanks to the accumulation of small isolated moments and details. 
Most tackle deprivation and the ability to get away. 
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz." 
"Replacement coffee, false aluminum, rubber imitation, bandages paper, wooden buttons." 
He goes on food replacement in Germany. 
He describes the "meat made of rice cooked in fat mutton (and finished with a false bone of wood); tobacco with dry roots and dried skin potato; soles of wooden shoes." 
He says that "837 permitted substitute meats are recorded in the production of sausages. There are 511 alternative cafes." 
Some stories deal with honour and courage. 
An American acknowledges its own drive against the savagery and says about the war: "You feel that, after all, this is what the men were intended, rather than sit in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and instead of pretending that such a veneer is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no barbarian behind your empesée shirt and cloutée. 
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that it likely to die, and that nobody will notice or pay attention. 
"When you are resigned to sacrifice themselves, we hope to have an audience," he wrote. 
It is unfortunately rather akin to "a condemned man strangled in secret." 
Other observations about the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror. 
"The conflict is becoming increasingly a story of economic competition," wrote Peter Englund, "a war between the factories." 
It captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the aviary at the beginning of the century: the mass murderer well-articulated and convinced ideologically, clothing, which carries out its butchery while being seated behind a desk." 
People act unexpectedly; there are so many basic behaviours of heroism. 
Peter Englund speaks of the soldiers who have tried to catch a venereal disease among prostitutes in order to avoid the service at the front. 
"We find the most grotesque expression in trade was due to gonorrhea, that soldiers buy and cover the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he wrote. 
"The most desperate eyes, which translates into a lifetime blindness." 
In the Swedish translation by Peter Graves, the prose of Peter Englund is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly suited to the task of humanity. 
In dozens of short scenes, it captures the way the war has "triggered exclusively uncontrollable forces: an extreme nationalism, a social revolution, an aversion to religion." 
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders have a war. 
The best books of the First World War are often indirect, such as "Great War and Modern Memory" (the Great War and Modern Memory) Paul Fussel, or "nothing new," Erich Maria Remarque, rather than complete. 
The book by Peter Englund is an unconventional pantheon. 
The end of the book is the most damning that I read in a fictionnelle. 
I am not going. 
But it is as if he had emerged from his book, seized your hands this page listing people and burned with a match. 
After a false start, a carefully planned operation 
