The union of school aid is suing the city for redundancies 
The union representing hundreds of school aides who have lost their jobs last month plans to launch Wednesday a trial in the city for discriminatory and unnecessary redundancies, the impact is disproportionate on schools with disadvantaged schoolchildren. 
The prosecution is probably the ultimate weapon of the union, the 37th District Council, to try to cancel the redundancies. 
Six hundred and seventy-two school aid coordinators of parents and other employees, part of the less well paid in the city, have lost their jobs on 7 October last year. The union leaders have compared these redundancies to a political revenge for not having left the city access to a fund for health care led by groups of workers, and that would have made it possible to close the budget gap in the spring. 
The municipal authorities have categorically denied the accusation. 
At a hearing of the City Council last month, Chancellor Dennis M. Walcott's Quarry said that the redundancies were part of the budget closed in June. 
A member of the Council has responded, stating that the redundancies of school aid were not specified in the budget. 
The officers of the 37th District Council have said that they would notice of claim, warning the Department of Education that he would be prosecuted; a press conference will be held Wednesday to formally announce the lawsuit to the Supreme Court in Manhattan. 
Dennis Walcott's quarry and the Department of Education of the city will be the defendant, the plaintiffs will be represented by eight laid-off workers, all black or Latin American origin, like most school aides who have lost their jobs. 
Elizabeth Thomas, spokesman of the legal department of the city, said that the municipality has not yet been able to see the reasons for the trial and cannot comment on the allegations. 
According to a draft complaint obtained by the New York Times, the union would capitalize on the number of redundancies in schools in the poorest parts of the city to support his complaint against unfair treatment, saying that the poorest schools would lose the most aid because of a regular underfunding. 
While there are no redundancies on Staten Island, and some barely in the institutions of Upper East Side and TriBeCa, 17 school aides have lost their jobs in the 23rd District of Brownsville, and 46 in the 8th and 9th Districts districts south of the Bronx. 
Noting the loss of five school aid on eight employed at Public School 36 in Harlem, where 68% of schoolchildren live in poverty, the prosecution claim that "this is not an area of wealthy parents who can get funds to fill the budget gap." 
The budget of the public school has been reduced from 3.26% this year. Funds have also been lost when the city has changed its calculation of the additional funding for each registration disadvantage. 
The union contended that the directors of schools have been misled by certain words in a memo authorizing the dismissal of coordinators of the parents. 
The memo was using the term "surge" to describe the action, even if "excess" described more generally move a teacher from a school to a group of available workers whose salaries are paid by the central office. 
According to the complaints, "sixty-six coordinators of parents have been made redundant," and "not only because of excess." 
Mission: Congress is an agreement on the issue of Libya 
Finally, it seems that the Republicans and Democrats have reached an agreement on Capitol Hill on the issue of the uprising in Libya. 
It took a successful uprising, the capture and the death of long-time dictator Muammar Gaddafi as well as the American involvement. 
The Committee on Foreign Relations of the Senate will take a decision next Tuesday, supported by President John Kerry (Democrat - Massachusetts), with Senators John McCain (Republican - Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent, Connecticut), applauding the Libyan people for their uprising and the American troops for their "courage." 
"This resolution is to honour the courage of the Libyans when they begin to rebuild their country," said John Kerry. 
"It is a bipartisan support for their democratic aspirations." 
The language may be harmless, but the debate on Libya has never been easy so far. 
This summer, legislators of both parties entered into conflict, as well as with the White House, on the wording of several resolutions to approve or not the US military role in the NATO mission in Libya. 
In June, Kerry and McCain have presented a resolution to authorize the limited use of US military forces in Libya. 
The bill was defeated by a wide bipartisan margin and has never been the subject of a vote in the Senate. 
But the same day of the failure of the bill, the Chamber of Deputies also rejected a measure to reduce the financing of US operations in Libya. 
The US mission therefore remained in a form of legislative purgatory - Congress sufficiently upset to criticize the management of the mission by Obama, but not enough to pull the rug. 
The indecision of Congress has been overtaken by events. 
Tripoli fell under the insurgents in August and Gaddafi was killed on 20 October. 
The NATO mission officially ended on 31 October. 
The Senate can now act. 
The resolution of the Committee on Foreign Relations "congratulate the Libyan people for their courage and determination for freedom" and "congratulates the men and women of the Armed Forces and their coalition partners engaged in military operations to protect the Libyan people for their courage and great professionalism." 
The resolution says "the national interest of the United States to achieve an irreversible and successful transition to democracy in Libya." 
The new measure will win the support of the Committee on Foreign Affairs of the Senate or divide legislators like last June? 
Senator and President of the Commission Richard D. Lugar (Independent) opposed the final version. 
His spokesman said on Monday that Richard D. Lugar had not yet read the latest version of the new project. 
Within the Capitol, the House must vote this week an amendment to the Constitution to achieve a balanced budget, a legislative priority for almost all Republicans in Congress, and some Democrats. 
The measure, supported by the Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget, or any other issue, to get a vote in the House or the Senate. 
Other legislators have so far failed to get their amendments, but it is not without having tried. 
The amendment Goodlatte is part of the 68 constitutional amendments have been presented to Congress on a wide range of subjects. 
Some are recurring - the same bill proposed in both the House and the Senate - and others are slight variations of a precedent. 
There are at least 15 versions in the House only of the amendment for a balanced budget, and another handful "control federal spending." 
Some of these bills are identical, but give their support - including the new Republicans who want to soften their CV - the chance to boast of being "the perpetrator" of such a measure. 
The law on the control of the budget (Budget Control Act) approved in August called for the House and Senate vote on the amendment for a balanced budget. 
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment. 
Beyond the budget, several members want to limit the number of mandates in which the members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (Democrat - New York) wants to lift the limit of two terms for presidents. 
Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Democrat - Illinois) has proposed a multitude of amendments guaranteeing the right to quality education and health care, among other subjects. 
An amendment banning marriage between same-sex is proposed, just as the amendment prohibiting the desecration of the flag. 
Some lawmakers also want to allow the repeal of federal laws if two-thirds of the states are opposed. 
As eager as were members to offer amendments, they are not as fast as in the past. 
During the 111th Congress, legislators have proposed 77 amendments, and introduced 66 at the 110th. 
The pace slowed from the early 1990s, when members were generally more than 150 amendments every two years, according to the figures provided by the library of the Senate. 
But these amendments were not much more successful than they have today. 
The last amendment to have been added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992 but proposed to Congress in 1789. 
