More pity than respect for the troops 
The event: a gala on Wall Street to reap millions of dollars for homeless veterans of the New York City. 
Kid Rock sang a ride on impotence, frustration and loss. 
Hundreds of soldiers, sailors, pilots and Marines around him. 
The crowd in tie is standing on its feet to cheer. 
"The military men and women are seen as heroes," said David Saltzman, organizer of the fundraising in the spring. 
A senior military officer present at the gala, which was also attended Admiral Mike Mullen, Chief of Staff of the United States, has seen the role of troops in different ways. 
"They have been presented as a kind of orphan," wrote the top military officer in an Email. 
I am sure that the organizers had good intentions. 
I know. 
But this was not just a pity. 
Absolutely contradictory impressions illustrate the difficult relations between the military and an American public passionate but often distant. 
Praise is lavished on the troops for their sacrifices. 
But they have a certain price, say a few soldiers. 
The public is increasingly as if he was sorry for the men and women in uniform. 
"We are not victims," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who led the troops in Iraq and will leave soon for Afghanistan. 
"But it seems that the only way to support us to lock ourselves in the role of unlucky minds." 
This is a very sensitive issue for the military leaders, who do not want to seem grateful or disagree with the public they serve. 
They realize that the anger of troops returners of the Vietnam War has been much worse. 
Thus, most conversations about the pity in confidence among the veterans. 
After the return of his two sons in the battle with the Marines, Colonel retired Mark Cancian has warned that the public would see their service from two perspectives. 
Some people would watch with respect because they have been confronted with insurgents and traveled to faraway places. 
Others are asking whether "a veteran angry and violent lies beneath the surface," said Cancian, who fought in Iraq and returned to work in the Government in Washington. 
When he was looking for a job, he said, he felt that a few people who talks called subtle if he would be able to keep under the stress of a demanding job in Washington immediately after his return from combat. 
"When you raise the subject of the service, you are confronted with negative impressions," recalls Colonel Cancian when he speaks to his sons. 
The military difficulties, in part, from the American indifference to the wars. 
Victories are rarely appreciated by a country unfamiliar with the army, which sees little direct benefits of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan. 
"As a nation, we no longer cherish the heroism in the same way as for the Second World War," said Lieutenant General David Barno, who led the troops in Afghanistan. 
Instead, the congratulations of politicians and the people focus largely on the depth of the suffering of a military. 
The troops are recognized for the number of periods of service endured, the number of lost friends or the extent of the injuries. 
The army faces increasing pressure to crack down on rapists 
This week, a crucial hearing will decide whether 28 men and women will go to trial against the army for alleged inaction on rape. 
If so, hundreds of complainants will prepare the next. 
The soldier of 1st Class Elizabeth Lyman was aged 25 years and 11 weeks pregnant the night she was raped by a soldier. 
C " was in October 2008. It returned to its barracks at Miramar Air Station, north of San Diego, after having dinner with a friend, when she met a colleague carrying a pack of beers. 
He was asked if he could join in his bedroom to drink a glass. 
"C" was a wake-up call, " says Elizabeth Lyman. 
But the Texane has set aside its concern. 
I thought: no, it was 19 years old. 
"It is Texas," she said. 
"I had to follow my intuition." 
A few minutes after entering the House of Elizabeth Lyman, the man grabbed her from behind, thrown on the ground and raped, claims. 
This week, on 18 November, Elizabeth Lyman and 27 other soldiers, some still in service and not others, will wait anxiously for the decision of justice in an historic trial that will take place in Arlington, Virginia, and who will decide whether a trial brought against the former Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will take place. 
They are accused of failing to halt the spread of rape in the military, thus going against the constitutional rights of soldiers. 
In February by Susan Burke, a lawyer in Washington, the trial was initially 17 plaintiffs. This number amounted to 28 months - 25 women and 3 men, all claiming to have been raped or sexually abused by fellow soldiers; they claim that the army has not investigated, prosecuted or provided adequate justice after the alleged attacks. 
Susan Burke says military galonnées, because the problem starts with them. 
"The army is a vertical structure," she said. 
"Who are the individuals in the position d" eradicate the culture of retaliation? Leaders. " 
The lawyer also says that since the month of February, she has been contacted by almost 400 other survivors, many of whom could be part of future prosecution. 
His strategy: instead of bringing together all the plaintiffs in this case - putting all his eggs in the same basket - it will start a trial, if necessary, to maintain the pressure. 
The defence team for the Department of Defense, led by the US attorney Neil McBride, filed a motion to dismiss the case. 
The court documents, obtained by Newsweek, detailing the defence strategy, and essentially the fact that the army cannot be pursued by soldiers in service or not for injuries in the armed forces. 
According to a 1950 decision of the Supreme Court, known as the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries to staff in active service. 
"The alleged evil is inherent in the military service of the complainants" indicate the documents. 
The Department of Defense has refused to make any comment. 
Things have changed since the 1950s. 
While women have still not, officially, the right to go to war, this distinction is recorded only on paper: the front lines of the recent wars are rarely only male. 
In Iraq as in Afghanistan, teams of soldiers women play an increasingly important role, especially to enter into contact with local women. 
The result: in these two wars, 150 women soldiers have lost their lives - two-thirds in combat. 
It is time for the army to modernize says Susan Burke. 
It is not alone in this battle: three other trials are underway. 
At the Yale Law School, the centre of legal services for veterans is preparing a case against the four main military academies for allegedly encouraging a misogynistic atmosphere. 
On the other hand, the non-profit foundation Vietnam Veterans of America is preparing a trial against the army, focusing on the diagnoses of "personality disorder" assigned to the victims of rape in order to give them leave - a relatively ordinary, according to the activists such as Anu Bhagwaru of the Service Women's Action Network for military women), a group for human rights. 
His group filed a lawsuit in December at the Veterans Administration, accusing them of discriminatory practices in the way of dealing with the requests for benefits for those who have been victims of a sexual assault in the service. 
Nine bills independent of each other have been presented to Congress by a bipartisan mix of senators and representatives, offering various solutions. 
In 2010, 3,158 sexual assaults have been recorded in the centre of intervention and prevention of sexual assault (Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office) of the Department of Defense. 
But it is well known that the number of sexual assaults is underestimated, according to its own estimate of the Pentagon, this figure represents approximately 13.5% of the 19,000 incidents this year. 
The report published in March is also looking at the percentage of lawsuits: in 2010, 20% of cases recorded in the army have been the subject of a trial - half of the percentage of the civil justice system. 
The plaintiffs in the case of Susan Burke described their assault as the first of a series of injuries. 
In the case of Lyman, she informed the military of rape less than an hour after the fact. 
That night, she said, he was asked to tell 11 times in detail his rape to various police officers, doctors and commanders. 
She has undergone a "rape kit" (literally a rape kit), and the blood of his attacker - due to a cut to his arm - was found in his bed. 
Six months later, in April 2009, Elizabeth Lyman sat before a judge, a trial in which it questioned his sexual relations with her boyfriend earlier the day of its aggression. 
Six people have testified as witnesses of morality for the perpetrator of the crime, which was eventually acquitted. 
"I remember the day when the verdict was made," says Elizabeth Lyman. 
"I thought that I was going to begin to have contractions. I am yelling at the court." 
"I have been placed in psychiatric unit, and when I left, I remember having told my commander," it was not his trial but mine. " 
Elizabeth Lyman has been forced to consult a military psychiatrist, who has come to diagnose a personality disorder, making it unfit for service. 
In January 2010, it has been referred under less than honorable terms, preventing him from receiving any benefit. 
Does the case Lyman and other complainants will or not, it is a long history, says John Turley, a professor of law at the Faculty of Law at the University of Washington. 
However, he says, "in my opinion, they should be able to move forward." 
Only this doctrine criticized since its introduction is between them and a verdict. 
I have always criticised the Feres doctrine. 
The army is decades behind because it does not have the same advantages and means of deterrence posed by responsibility. 
"The odds are heavily against them... but it is important that they try," he said. 
These things change only when the right have the will to fight. 
If the trial is not in their favour, Susan Burke, the lawyer for the plaintiffs, will bring together hundreds of other plaintiffs for other trials. 
"We will continue to fight against the army on this issue so that there will be no reform," she says. 
