The walls have eyes: researchers study on Facebook 
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy expressing his anti-immigration views online. 
On Monday, Breivik, who acknowledged having been made a killing in Norway in July, leaving 77 victims, was facing his first trial. 
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being in cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, to discuss with some of the millions of nationalists who support the right-wing groups on social networking sites. 
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers want to learn more about these people. 
But how do we find? 
Easy... so log you on Facebook. 
"We realized that it was not so difficult to find them," says Jamie Bartlett, principal author of a report published recently by the think-tank DEMOS on the digital populism in Europe. 
Facebook is full of personal information, said Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they seek with scientific precision - the way in which the marketers are doing so for years. 
The team of Jamie Bartlett has discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe, it has targeted with announcements, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invite users to respond to an inquiry. The questions were asked about their level of education, their attitudes toward violence and their optimism about their own future. 
Coming into contact with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues have interviewed 10,000 supporters of 14 right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office. 
"This is a new way of doing research," says Jamie Bartlett. 
Some results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are men, young and against immigration. 
But surprisingly, "those who combine activism online and off-line are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen." 
The study of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook has become the new essential tool in the hands of scientists. 
Think-tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the issues that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to the "I love," publications on the walls and updated statutes. 
With more than 800 million active users who add content per day on average, the "data we call supernovae" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research that the name of the site appears in the title of almost 800% over the last five years. 
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people that you could not walk in the street. 
"Before, when you try to carry out investigations into the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify." 
"You have to go to the party, but they have never allowed to enter," says Jamie Bartlett. 
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information." 
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and treat health and social problems. 
According to a recent study of D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, the young students who spoke on Facebook of their exploits while intoxicated had a lot more likely to be alcoholics than discreet students. 
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as advisers, could monitor the site and intervene to help possibly a student whose status would speak too often. 
"You can't deal with a problem if you do not diagnostiquez," Dimitri Christakis, coauthor of Megan Moreno and director of the centre for health, behaviour and development of children at the Research Institute for children located in Seattle, says the Washington Post. 
"We know how to identify children at risk, and in another case not recognized." 
Facebook also constantly accessing information from its users. 
The site team has studied the statistics concerning the situation lover and the day of Saint Valentine, the rate of participation in the midterm elections in 2010 and a national happiness index (thanks to the only available information - the champions of the digital freedom have long argued that the site could make available its treasure trove of data to other people for research purposes). 
But users of Facebook know that the site that they like or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to have access to your information. 
But what happens when users of Facebook are part of an investigation that they have not even heard? 
While researchers have clear instructions on how to collect information other than via the Internet, it is anything else online. 
"I do not believe that a large number of users have already thought to the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn's, a sociologist at the Knowledge Lab in London, according to a study in 2006 that he has been looking at the Facebook walls of his students. 
"As far as they know, the exchanges were seen only by their friends." 
Then comes the question of methodology. 
Even without passing through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study to be completely honest. 
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on the wall of a user. 
"What you say about Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things," says Neil Selwyn's. 
That is why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn's believes that a notebook and a pen remain the best tools that can be used. 
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with the people," he said. 
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and the social, it is not in front of a computer." 
"Cold and inhumane": first appearance of Anders Behring Breivik 
Anders Behring Breivik, the man who has admitted having organised the two attacks that have been 77 deaths in Norway this summer, was described as a "resistance" fighter during his first appearance at the trial which is taking place in Oslo. 
