"With regard to the jurisdiction of the court, I reject, because your mandate of organizations supporting an ideology of hatred and because it supports multiculturalism." 
"I acknowledge the facts, but I do not plead guilty." 
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during this monologue because he "didn't want to give him the opportunity to use this trial to express his opinions." 
For the same reason, he has refused to allow Breivik, who has brought with him a speech on paper, talk to the relatives of the victims at the end of the hearing. 
Judge Nesheim has also asked the Police Breivik detain 12 weeks, he was forbidden to talk to the media for four weeks and warned that the authorities would monitor very closely all visits and correspondence for eight weeks. 
Thirty relatives of survivors and victims were present at the hearing. 
Some came in the hope of watching Breivik in their eyes, others to be sure that he would be placed behind bars. 
All attended the hearing in order to see the end of the trial. 
"I have found cold and inhuman," said a survivor of Utoya to the Norwegian television channel NRK. 
"I was not comfortable, but I have a little advanced after having seen and heard the suspect." 
Dressed in a dark suit and a blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the trial, he looked at the journalists and the survivors in the eye by entering and leaving the court. 
Despite the bizarre idea that Breivik belongs to a broad movement of "resistance," the judge has determined that he was not crazy; he also said that there is no evidence that he acted with accomplices. 
The attacks on 22 July appear to be the work of an extremist rather than a whole group of radicals, resulting in criticism - absolutely not perhaps some. 
But this does not reduce the grief and confusion felt by the entire nation. 
"I would have preferred that it looks like a monster, but this is not the case," said a parent of a victim. 
"It would have been much easier." 
Seven lessons from the interview lost Steve Jobs, the film this week 
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, some have compared to Henry Ford - characterised by the technical genius and inventor of the modern computer. 
But what Apple fans can find more revealing in an interview with Steve Jobs recovered recently and which will be broadcast this week in the first part of a film on the major markets, is how this creative spirit had understood the process and work flow of products. 
It was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. It had a hippie, but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a ameliorative charts - a man who believed that many business leaders had a "disease suggesting that a brilliant idea is 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work between a brilliant idea for a product of exception." 
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds." This series chronicles the birth of the computer, and he sits down for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation. 
At that time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet. 
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he says that the main copies have been lost in transport. 
It is only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video is found in the garage of the director. 
This video, slightly bulging, is the basis of the 68 minutes film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be broadcast to the cinema next Wednesday and Thursday. 
For someone known to hate depth-interviews, Steve Jobs seems surprisingly enthusiastic to expose technological philosophies and business strategies. 
And incredibly attentive. 
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to give a precise answer. 
There are also moments when perfectionism of Steve Jobs resurfaced, where he seems anxious to hear the issues of Cringely, giving him shots of elbow to speed up and move to questions or issues of greater importance. 
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prescient about Lost Interview: Steve Jobs assesses what he considers good or bad in other businesses and expressed its own vision on the future of computing. 
It is one thing to read the posthumous assessments of the career of Steve Jobs, but there is something inspiring about the man that we see here, the anxiety dreamer on the eve of greatness. 
He has a vision of how things can be and should be. 
He said then. 
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview: 
On the way in which he has learned to run a business: 
"During all these years, I have always asked:" why are you doing things? "And the answers are always the same: ' Oh, just because we need to do." 
No one knows why, no one is thinking about deep things in a company. 
This is what I discovered. 
Steve Jobs is giving details on its efforts to simplify accounting for Apple. 
Puzzled as to how the costs were recorded - it often begins with a "standard cost" assessed to nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he has developed an automated plant that guaranteed the precise calculation of trade costs. 
The opportunity to play a round on the Pope: 
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "blue box" that he has created with Steve others - a device that was used to hack into telephone networks and call free long distance. 
The device has been the subject of many written beforehand, but the euphoria of Steve Jobs here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious. 
He describes how he and others have tested the box using a public telephone, and then connecting from one network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible. 
"We enveloppions the ball of different things a half-dozen times and you hurliez in the public telephone and you arrived a minute later to the public telephone," said Jobs, chuckling. 
"We were young and thanks to the Blue Box, we learned that we could ourselves create something capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure in the world." 
We do not know much, but we have managed to invent a small thing capable of controlling great things; it was an incredible lesson, and I do not believe that Apple would have existed without it. 
Steve Jobs is telling a wonderful round that he and others have developed: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night by impersonating Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope. 
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go crazy laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened. 
His love with technology (and Bill Hewlett): 
At the age of 12 years, the hunt for spare parts to produce a fréquencemètre, he wants the number of Bill Hewlett in the directory and a quick phone call. 
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard. 
"This has had a remarkable influence on me," was the only company that I had seen at this stage and it formed my definition of a business and how employees are treated. " 
Steve Jobs has subsequently become one of the employees to visit the research laboratories of the company, located in Palo Alto, where he found the "first ever desktop." 
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small CRT. I fell in love. 
The teenager was returned at HP and began to write programs for this machine. 
Improvisation of innovation: 
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs speaks to invent new products on a head. 
At the beginning of his career, when he moved to sell a few circuit boards, a customer asked to assemble a complete computer. 
Working at only 30 days of credit, he must deal with the assembly and delivery of finished devices. 
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties in developing a computer mouse: 
"I remember big disputes... I yelled above arguing that it would take five years to produce a mouse that would cost $300] I have had enough, I went out and went to see a designer." 
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to make $15, which was incredibly reliable. 
Large companies that burn out: 
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs anticipated how many industrial leaders would be wrong and losing control of their market share. 
"If you work for IBM or Xerox, you better copier or printer, and after"? 
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success. 
Sales and marketing can evolve, so it is these types of people who end up leading companies and staff are put to the gap in decision-making. 
The genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by those who cannot imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product - the manual work required. 
This is what happened at Xerox... 
Xerox could hold all the computer industry. 
It could have done ten times its current size, Xerox would have been the Microsoft in the 1990s... 
They have snatched defeat to victory. 
On innovation as an art form: 
"A huge amount of manual work between a brilliant idea of an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it is changing and growing." 
You learn a lot about its intricacies. 
There are compromises to do... some things that you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories, too. 
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling. 
Finally, the decisions are made by personal taste; it is to try to explain the best products that men have created, and to try to bring these things to the product that you create. 
Picasso said that good artists copy and that the great artists steal. 
We have always been ashamed to steal good ideas. 
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional: the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologistes, historians, who were simply the best computer scientists in the world. 
Except for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area. 
