The day when the Supreme Court meets behind closed doors to examine the issue of political discord, whether the opposition to the law of President Obama's health will be heard, two of its judges, Scalia and Clarence Thomas, have been spotted at a dinner sponsored by the firm of lawyers who will defend the case before the High Court. 
The event was last Thursday, when the nine judges met for a conference to discuss petitions for review. 
One of the cases in question concerned a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the reform of health care ambitious passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying point for conservative activists at the national level. 
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, in effect, a monumental 5h30 argument is expected in March, and the result will probably contribute to the destabilisation of the 2012 presidential race, which will be growing at a time when the court's decision will be made. 
The lawyer before the court and argued on the rejection of the law, will probably be Paul Clement, who has served as Solicitor General of the United States during the administration of George W. Bush. 
The legal firm of Clément, PLLC Bancroft, has been part of the two dozen firms that have helped to sponsor the annual dinner of the Fédéraliste Society (Federalist Society), a long-standing group dedicated to defending the conservative legal principles. 
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that have challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business (National Federation of Independent Business). 
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the dispute. 
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court's conference on the matter. 
There is, among other things, Mitch McConnell, top Republican of the Senate and opponent of the health law. 
The star invited to the dinner? Scalia and Thomas. 
This is not new: the two judges were present at the events of the Fédéraliste Society for years. 
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics. 
In fact, the judges are exempt from code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges. 
If they were, they probably argumenteraient by the Code of Canon 4C, which states: "A judge can attend fund-raising organizations linked to the law and that the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honour, or appearing on the agenda of such an event." 
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas in the vicinity of two lawyers in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm the activists of government ethics. 
"This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the Court should respect the same rules that apply to all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause. 
"The judges were drinking and were having dinner and a fundraising gala with lawyers who have cases pending before the court." 
Their presence and their participation in the fundraising of this event dismantle any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable. 
Scalia and Thomas have shown little regard for the criticism that they mix too easily the affairs of the court with the agenda of groups such as the Fédéraliste Society. 
And the wife of Thomas, Ginni, is a conservative activist profile. 
Moreover, the Conservatives claim that it is the judge Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, and not Scalia and Thomas. 
Kagan was Solicitor General of the Obama administration when the first opposition to the law have been brought to the level of the Court of First Instance. 
His critics have pressed for Kagan recused to hear the case, saying that it had too much invested in the defence of the law to be impartial. 
Kagan has given no indication that it would do so. 
