The amount of these six devices more than a billion dollars. 
"This is clearly very positive for Boeing," said Neal Dihora, analyst at Morningstar. 
"These clients in particular have an immense value." 
In the Middle East, the oil-producing countries have a lot of their airlines. 
They have therefore not only the means to pay for these planes, but a rise in the price of fuel - usually detrimental for airlines because it represents their most important costs - would be less harmful because the country would gain money with the rise in oil prices. 
This is an important point because these companies will be less likely than others to cancel or postpone their orders for aircraft when the oil price rises, said Dihora. 
"They have a natural hedge," he said. 
The order Emirates strengthens the dominance of Boeing wide-body aircraft and helps to curb the encroachment of the Airbus competitor with his plane A350. 
