LADS urges Asia to help the eurozone 
The Asian Development Bank has called on India and China to prepare to help the eurozone out of the crisis of sovereign debt to avoid a long-term decline that would prevent the development of the Asian economy. 
Rajat Nag, the Director General of LADS based in Manila, said that the two economic powers to the fastest growing in the world should "do everything in their power" to accelerate the recovery of the monetary zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements. 
He warned the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India and China) to look at the difficulties of Europe of a "indifferent eye" and pointed out that Asian financial support alongside leaders and resources of Europe would avoid a long-term collapse of the global economy. 
"We are all together in this crisis." 
"Therefore anyone can help Europe to emerge from the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times in an interview during the Economic Forum World in Bombay. 
"Asia can be protected" at some point, but it is not immune. " 
"So if China and India can help, that nothing prevents." 
In recent months, the euro area has been severely shaken by a crisis of sovereign debt. 
Recently, the cost of borrowing Italian dangerously soared and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned. 
The burgeoning crisis of sovereign debt in Europe has spurred the fear that the global economy falls into recession, and prompted the appeal of the major emerging economies to come together to help the euro area to find a solution. 
Mr. Nag has hopes that the IMF would provide any assistance, but he has also said that this bilateral assistance - such as buying the obligations of the financial rescue funds from the United States, the European Financial Stability Fund - offered greater power in negotiations with the Asian partners in Europe. 
Anand Sharma, the Minister of Trade and Industry of India, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the eurozone since its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a decline in arrivals of foreign capital. 
"Nobody wants the eurozone remains unstable and turbulent," he said. 
"We have monumental challenges ahead and we must maintain a high level of growth." 
"This is not a choice, it is an imperative, because where would we work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?" 
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help European rich when they face their own major economic challenges. 
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, has said that it would be politically very difficult to accept aid from Europe to the 1.2 billion Indians, including at least 800,000 live on $2 a day or less. 
"One day, they will discover that the Greeks retire at 50 years and that they go on holiday in the sun and they will find it difficult to swallow," he said. 
Lee Howell, the chairman of the World Economic Forum, has also asked why the reserves of India should be used to keep many well-paid Greek officials in poorly managed jobs that generate losses, as in the rail sector. 
Mr. Nag said that the crisis in the eurozone could cause "significant repercussions" across Asia. 
Forecasts of LADS economic growth of 7.5% in Asia in 2011/2012 now face "the risk of loss" because of the European threat. 
He pointed out that vulnerable emerging markets needed "develop" contingency plans " to protect themselves from an economic downturn and massive leakage of capital. 
Severe warnings from the Pentagon about the potential cuts in defence 
The Secretary of Defense, Leon Panetta, has upped the pressure on the Congress on Monday, warning that the impending automatic cuts would undermine national security. It triggered a chain reaction financial corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, from gatherings of civilians. 
The Pentagon digests already $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional amount of $600 or more cuts is imminent if the Congress does not reach an agreement on spending. 
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating to the department," said Panetta in a letter to Senators John McCain, R- Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R- South Carolina. 
He said that the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in the so-called sequestration, would lead to 23% of reductions as well as the freezing of many new projects. 
"A significant reduction, and applied indiscriminately, would make most of our ships and our unfeasible construction projects - you cannot buy three quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously undermine other efforts to modernize," Panetta wrote to senators. 
"We would also have to separate a number of our civilian personnel, and because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we should almost certainly send civilians leave without pay in order to achieve the objective." 
"These changes would undermine the faith of those who support our military and seriously alter our preparation." 
The cuts would affect possibly troops, continues Panetta. 
"Although funding in wartime contingency operations abroad is not directly affected by the kidnapping, the war effort would be negatively affected by the serious disturbances in the core budgets," said Panetta. 
"The contractor would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of contracts that support the war." 
"The staff managing salaries would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers of war, and the legal and political support would be disrupted." 
The two senators wrote to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details about the potential impact of automatic cuts in the Ministry of Defence. 
"The result of a kidnapping on the Department of Defense would trigger a rapid decline in the US as the world's undisputed leader of the military power." 
"We are fiercely opposed to this drastic action," said the senators in a joint communiqué on Monday afternoon at the publication of the letter to Panetta. 
"This is not a consequence with which we can live, and it is certainly not the one that we should impose." 
"Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen." 
The letter from Panetta and the recent warnings of senators are increasing the pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon cuts, remains to be seen. 
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even if he succeeded himself at the highest position in the Pentagon with years of expertise in the budget to Congress and the White House and knowing that he was faced with difficult choices. 
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a bleak picture of what might occur - a military with a shell, but no core. 
"It is a ship without sailors." 
"It is a brigade without bullets." 
"It is a fighter plane, without enough trained pilots." 
"It is a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that do not have enough trained soldiers capable of accomplishing the mission," said Panetta in his opening remarks at the Pentagon. 
"It is a force depressed, poorly prepared and unable to cope with potential adversaries." 
"De facto, it invites aggression. 
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta outlined specifically how new reductions could "generate significant operational risks: deadline for responding to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and risk unacceptable in future combat operations." 
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defence projects could go to the axe, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning. 
The list included the Fighter F-35 Joint Strike, a new bomber planned, the new-generation ballistic submarine, the new gunship coastline and the new ground vehicle, which would replace the Humvee of the army and navy. 
Put an end to the development and testing of the F-35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but his supporters say that it is an essential step to improve and respond to potential threats from China and other rivals. 
How can we identify a lie 
A look at the recent headlines indicates how deception and lies are ubiquitous in everyday life. 
The Republican nominee for president Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying. 
Penn State administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly covered reports a football coach retired sexually assaulted boys. 
Last week President Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone saying to US President Barack Obama that the Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar. 
The lie has destroyed careers and country convulsé. 
The New York congressman and celebrity Internet Anthony Weiner, went for a fool by quickly issuing denials contradicted by evidence. 
The former candidate for the presidency John Edwards has been accused of violations of the financing of campaigns related to the coverage of an extramarital affair. 
And then, no one who experienced history will never forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying in his second term on his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky affair. 
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion. 
There have been cases where teachers have given the test answers to students in order to get on their assessments of performance. 
The mentors who should teach the contrary send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable. 
How much deception? 
On a given day, the studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies. 
In fact, many of them are pious lies. 
Another study showed that foreigners will lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting. 
Detect or identify lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons. 
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to get who said: "I haven't been," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities have conducted a thorough search for such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology. 
One of the results of research is that the most ancient myths about the lies have been démystifiés. 
The liars you look in the eye. 
They are not bégayent, feeling or not always. 
Do not conclude that the liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover. 
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the declaration, facial expressions, the formation of the issue and the response time. 
I spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and still emerge from the knowledge of the deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern competence that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or management. 
Good liars are adept at reading others, comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively sensing how others perceive them. 
We know from research that the extroverted lie more than introverted men say more lies "citizen-centred" while women say more lies "focused on the other" - usually to protect the feelings of someone - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge). 
We also know that if you are seen as a calling, others will feel less guilty of lying to you. 
How can you tell if someone is lying? 
First, look at the normal behaviour of your subject. 
This is what is called "benchmarks." 
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring future changes. 
Look at the shape of your subject, laughter, voice quality. 
You need to know if someone normally hit his feet constantly in order to not launch unfair accusations when you see Slinging feet in the middle of the meeting. 
Then look for signs of misleading verbal and non-verbal behaviour. 
Consider these indices as red flags, not evidence of deception. 
Misleading people can stop the upper body when they try to remember their history, they can hold their feet to the door, leaning out, change significantly posture or present a relief "interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions. 
The interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview was completed just to try to trigger the reaction after the interview. 
Also, look at the vocabulary of your subject. 
The famous Scott Peterson skidded through the past while pretending that his wife murdered were alive, triggering a national search to find. 
Misleading individuals can also use a strong language: "I have not had sexual relations with that woman... Ms. Lewinsky's dress' or repeat entirely a difficult question. 
The most common verbal indicators are subtle. 
Someone can use a lot of "bush" in its response to a difficult question: "Well... to say... if I remember... to my knowledge." 
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag. 
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize the deception is possible. 
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid victimization by hustlers in their personal and professional lives. 
The controversial pipeline will be diverted after the threat of late approval of the US 
A few days after the Obama administration has threatened to delay the approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico - provoking the anger of unions while appeasing environmentalists - the company seeking to build the pipeline says that it is ready to redirect the project back on track. 
TransCanada said Monday evening that it will move the projected pipeline out of the area ecologically sensitive dunes of Nebraska, and is confident that the project will win its approval. 
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Capitol Nebraska. 
The official, Alex Pourbax, says that the company remains confident that it will eventually obtain the approval of a pipeline, but with a different route. 
This follows the announcement by the State Department last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal permit for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid areas of the dunes of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, vast underground water sources. 
"It is a real way forward," said Terry Lee, a Republican from Nebraska to Fox News. 
The new review commissioned by the Department of State would probably have postponed any decision until 2013, after the elections next year, although officials deny the involvement of politics in the decision. 
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the decision of the Department of State, and he expressed his support. 
The 2,735 kilometers pipeline extending from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico. 
It would carry 700,000 barrels per day from the province of Alberta to Texas refineries. 
To do so, it would cross six states. 
He is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, which have focused on the 20,000 estimated jobs related to the pipeline. 
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan have lobbied for a law to force the remoteness of the region of Sand Hills and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation. 
The environmental impact study of the State Department has found that the project would have only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry has said that the Inspector General of the Department has ordered a separate investigation of the review process focused on two issues. 
One is that a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was a campaign adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, would represent a conflict of interest in the program. 
The other is whether a company that has been hired to conduct the initial study was an inappropriate choice by its relationship to TransCanada. 
