The Court valid "analogue" in Mexico by 2015 
The substitution of analogue signales is one of the largest exchange rates that the world has suffered the last few years 
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have made against the presidential decree that advance the so-called "digital divide" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes needed to invalidate have not been met. 
A minority of four ministers, attached the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón has not exceeded his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital television. 
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force. 
The draft, drawn up by the Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, has proposed the declaration of the decree as constitutional, because of the fact that the rules on radio and television is an award reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve. 
The draft voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero. 
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to contest the decree and acknowledging complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by the government for the digital transition. 
The plenary session of ministers resolved also dismiss the complaint by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project with the Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible. 
In his speech, the minister president said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive branch cannot structure through general standards that the public administration is preparing. 
"I do not think it would affect the autonomy of the regulator," and he pointed out that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has constitutional mandate the direction of the state. 
The substitution of signales analog by digital signales is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years, and this is reflected in a better exploitation of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels. 
Postponing the change, argued, would postpone the benefits of digitisation which implies a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security." 
These questions, noted, "require the operation of any establishes a system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state, includes a group of powers that the Constitution gives the power of the executive branch of the state." 
He recalled that a large number of countries throughout the world have already finished the digital transition, and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had the highly specialized technical bodies. 
We cannot conclude that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it provides in the administrative sphere laws issued by the Législative himself. 
The possibility of a "vote by vote" recount in Michoacán 
According to the data highlighted by PERs, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 6 thousand total 74 minutes. 
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in relation to the electoral trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Électoraux Results Program background (PER) the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 6 thousand 74 minutes total. 
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (AEI), María de los ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, the past 9 November, the electoral body has approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards to the federal reforms in electoral matters. 
We will remember that Michoacán has not licensed nor its constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Act of Justice, while the Congress of the State has approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline so that this trial can enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel failed its publication in time by the Law of the Official Journal of the state, with the argument that he had some objections. 
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Législative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the representative of the state for constitutional reforms, because it does not have the right to "sanction or challenge." 
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote," María de los ángeles Llanderal said that with the approval of the guidelines by the General Council of AEI it will be possible to achieve the total and partial counting of votes by the local electoral body. 
Thus, the partial count of votes, one or several electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting in the case of the ballot box is not for the president; or there are obvious errors or alterations minutes. 
In addition, the total count of votes in all ballot boxes from the election can be achieved when there is an indication of the fact that the difference between the supposed winner of the election and the one who won the second place in the poll is equal to or below a percentage point; at the beginning of the session is a petition by the representative of the party and/or coalition that has presented the second of the candidates reported. 
The total count of the vote can be achieved if at the end of the joint statement makes clear that the difference between the supposed winner and the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is a petition by the representative of the political party whose candidate came second, cases in which one will exclude the electoral packets that have been subject to the partial count. 
It is worth mentioning that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PPRD, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16%, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes. 
