The new Italian government will be formed Wednesday 
The Prime Minister designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought this country to the brink of economic disaster 
The Prime Minister designate, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the president of Italy to present the new government will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and has jeopardized the entire euro zone. 
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the government. 
It is expected that he presents a cabinet in its majorities by technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume his post. 
Monti said that he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government. 
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for journalists. 
Monti has not explicitly said that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome. 
The "framework is now well mapped out," he added. 
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of its debt to levels impossible to sustain. 
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by the European leaders to recover confidence in Italy that had been affected. 
Underlining the pressure on Monti to dispatch, the instability of the markets placed the Italian BTP bond yield 10 years above 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland have duu be saved. 
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian Confindustria, told the media after his meeting with Monti: "We said that we would support a lot of this government." 
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy in this emergency situation. 
The chances of success of Monti have been greatly boosted by the support of the LDP party of Silvio Berlusconi, which the crisis has forced to resign last Saturday. 
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good outcome," said the press Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party. 
The support of PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members opposed to the Government of majority technocrat, Monti. 
Parliamentary support 
The new government of Monti must have a strong parliamentary support to implement what will probably be reforms of unpopular austerity. 
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets. 
The Italian association of foreign banks has added to the pressure by observing that a failure of Monti would be a disaster. 
Monti began Monday its consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and juvenile and women's organizations. 
He will end his tour of meetings on Tuesday night. 
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who has allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis. 
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt are now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister. 
Save Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, it would be too much for the financial defences current euro zone. 
Monti said that his government should persist in future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions on the fact that the politicians only give them time to implement the reforms before bringing forward the elections. 
Monti said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist on the fact that it must be formed only by specialists, an index of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure. 
Political sources have indicated that the mutual suspicions and disagreements between the parties complicate the trial to include political figures. 
