According to the local media, Mujica is seeking to persuade Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France, which took place when the French agent, Nicolas Sarkozy, has included the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes. 
In his speech, Sarkozy has threatened to exclude from the international community countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that has provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations of its ambassador to this European country. 
Mexico chairs since November the G20, a group of developed and emerging countries in the world, and with the South American country since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation. 
The Uruguayan government has tried the last few years to send the implementation of the agreements to exchange tax to get out of the "brand name knock-off list" of the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), integrated by countries not to enforce all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters. 
On the trade front, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Free Trade Treaty (TLC), which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations. 
