Japan renait after the earthquake 
GDP rose 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of decline in the beginning of March 
Since the month of March, the Japanese economy was paralysed, fragile even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe of the Japanese country since the Second World War. 
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo have calculated the loss to 300 million, a blow that, in spite of the difficult global context, seems to be mitigated. 
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September have been used for closure: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and a 6% annualized rate. 
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - requires, in addition, the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010. 
The recovery is due, in part, by the resumption of purchases of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami. 
In fact, companies have increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditures for January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increases. 
However, the true stimulate the Japanese economy is based solely on the Keynesian stimulus that calls to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the deficiencies to grow from scratch. 
Japan woke up mainly due to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japanese GDP. 
This variable increased 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities. 
The stigma of the yen 
Tokyo was given to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become a "values refuge" elected by investors who are fleeing the debt crisis in eurozone and unrest forecasts of the United States, a privilege hanging like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies. 
With a divided, the products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic slack is determined by the health of large technology groups. 
Toyota or Sony, for example, have been responsible for their poor results between July and September the assessment of the yen. 
While the markets continue their seats in the peripheral countries of the EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not drop the guard. 
"We must follow the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa. 
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging. 
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of the member countries have presented in September clearer signals of economic slowdown. 
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points in the global economy has highlighted that the major powers are limited. 
Because it dropped four decimal points up to $100.4 points, compared to $100.8 in August. 
Eurozone has even been above the average, which is in the 100, dropping eight decimal points to 99.13 points. 
