As in other cases, the effects of announcement seem somewhat disproportionate with the reality of fraud to the work stoppages. 
This is indeed the subject since 2002 to constant monitoring and offensive policies, which are most often paid off. 
The French no more ill than elsewhere in Europe. 
We first focus on the national figures. 
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (NHIF), more than 237 million euros per diem were issued in 2006. 
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in economics of health, daily allowances accounted for in 2008 5% of health spending, with 11.3 billion euros. 
On this amount, 46% were maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% were sickness rates, or 6.2 billion euros. 
And therefore 2.5% of health spending. 
In 2010, the French have experienced an average 14.5 days of work stoppage, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the group Alma Consulting. 
An average conceals some differences: another survey, published in 2007 by the Career Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any day to stop disease. 
Another study, this time of medicare, states that in 2010, 37% of sickness rates were less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% of 15 days a month, 15% from one to three months and 11% above. 
When compared with their European neighbours, employees are no more likely than elsewhere to work stoppages. 
A lengthy study conducted in 2010 by two researchers from the CNRS showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall rate of absence (for reasons of health or not), in France, between 10% and 11%, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the UK or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands. 
Fraud judgments disease represents very little undeclared work. 
With regard to fraud, it reached only a small scale. 
The strengthening of the legislation since 2002 that the controls are systematic on sickness rates of more than 45 days. 
In 2008, about 1.5 million checks, the NHIF found that 13% of the 285,000 made for short-term judgments were "unjustified or too long," or 37,050 cases. 
In the case of the judgments of more than 45 days, systematically monitored, there were 11% of cases "inappropriate or unwarranted" about 1.2 million, or 132,000. 
In total, 169,000 cases "unjustified," over several million workers who have been stopping disease. 
A figure that represents very little, for example, that of undeclared work. 
According to the UMP MP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of loss of tax revenue per year, which is more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud in the past. 
