We need to legalise euthanasia and assisted suicide, said a committee of experts 
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada 
In the area of palliative care, the committee is demanding that governments, healthcare institutions, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer. 
Society lives in denial of death. 
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk with their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make provisions to this effect. 
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report from the Royal Society of Canada, involving six experts in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine. 
The Committee recommends the government to amend the Criminal Code to permit assisted suicide and euthanasia, when this choice is required, with a patient deemed competent to take such a decision. 
First-off, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world. 
If Canada is ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death." 
Or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada. 
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital. 
Overall, the country is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths occurring in the hospital. 
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said it will change the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide. 
However, according to the experts, who have also gone through all the countries where these approaches are legalised or decriminalised, there is no evidence that this leads to decriminalization of abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on persons not competent or not willing. 
On the contrary, stated yesterday by teleconference Jocelyn Downie, author of the report, would be more cases of these excesses specifically in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalised. 
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal." 
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," said Jocelyn Downie. 
Canadians in favour of euthanasia 
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow people to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010. 
And 66% believe that legalising euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled has less value. 
As for people who have assisted suicide, asked to 41% that they should not be prosecuted. 
In terms of maintaining or cessation of care to a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report. 
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is stated in the Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a refusal legally valid is not criminal. 
The Committee of Experts also requires that health professionals are trained in the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution. 
In the area of palliative care, the committee is demanding that governments, healthcare institutions, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer. 
Finally, in terms of palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce the physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it is subject to the same procedures. 
Reservations from other experts 
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the report of experts from the Royal Society of Canada. 
Pierre Deschamps, an expert in health law, called "extreme" the position of experts signatories of the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia for the terminally ill. 
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and who would have more than 18 years could ask for help to commit suicide," said Ms. Fields, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report. 
Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report appear to put the autonomy of the person above all other values that contribute to the social fabric of society. 
"In society, he said, there are limitations and constraints." 
The law expert Margaret Somerville has also expressed "strong opposition" to the conclusions of the report, which she called "manifest pro-euthanasie." 
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, particularly challenged the data in the report about the lack of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide were legalised in the Netherlands and Oregon. 
