At a press conference, the Syrian Foreign Minister Walid imprisonment has estimated that the country is "heading towards the end of the crisis." 
He has strongly reacted to the decision of the Arab League to suspend Damascus of its work, which is "a very dangerous step." 
Syria "does not waver," he added, assuring that "the ourdis conspiracies against Syria will fail." 
After its decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is currently studying a "mechanism to protect civilians" and wants to send 500 members of Arab organizations of human rights, media and military observers in the country. 
The French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also favored the sending of observers from the UN to help protect civilians of the repression of the regime that he locks himself in the "paranoia." 
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled for tomorrow in Rabat to take stock of the implementation of the exit plan decided on 2 November, including the withdrawal of the armed forces of the cities plagued by the dispute and the release of demonstrators arrested. 
The Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs, Sergei Lavrov, said yesterday "incorrect" the decision of the Arab League, while China urged Syria to implement the exit plan, while refraining from supporting possible sanctions against Damascus. 
Italy 
Monti markets and sacrifices to the Italians 
The future leader of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has called for a little time for the markets to train his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifices," in order to recover the lost credibility in the final months of the Berlusconi government. 
The former European Commissioner was in discussion with the political parties yesterday before meeting today the trade unions and employers. 
It should put in place a firm relatively composed of technocrats from outside Parliament. 
"Monti has spoken of an important program with a lot of sacrifices," said Francesco the member of one of the many small groups engaged in the talks, after having met with the President of the Council appointed. 
The President of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, for his part said expect that Mario Monti sought by Friday a vote of confidence in Parliament to ensure that the new government has sufficient support. 
The consultations will be completed by the presentation by Mr. Monti of a restricted list, perhaps a dozen ministers, the head of state, Giorgio Napolitano. 
Mr. Monti commented on the nervousness of stock and bond markets yesterday, asking them time. 
"Democracy, there are timelines" to prepare a government and its agenda, he stressed, saying "certain that the markets will be patient and understand." 
His appointment by the president was initially welcomed by the markets, but the concern has regained the upper hand, especially after an unexpected drop in industrial production in the euro area in September. 
The prime minister should be a team consisting mainly of technocrats, although he stressed that he wants to include "policies." 
The new government must last until 2013, the date of the next parliamentary elections, he said. 
According to the President of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new government will have the confidence of Parliament by Friday. 
Mr. Monti pledged, once in office, to work in the emergency and in order that Italy "protagonist" in Europe. 
A spokesman for European Commissioner Olli Rehn stressed that "even with a new government, our diagnosis on the Italian economy does not change." 
The EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its objective of budgetary balance by 2013 despite the austerity plans adopted in recent months, called for new austerity measures. 
The "boss of bosses" Italian Emma Marcegaglia, who will be on Tuesday, has also insisted on the need to revive the economy, "because a country that has no growth cannot meet the parameters of deficit." 
Mr. Monti, known for his competence and independence as a European commissioner (1994-2004), represents a "change of epoch" for Italy after 17 years of "berlusconisme," the "teacher" symbolizing "the serious challenge" and "other Italy," according to the editorialists. 
The great unknown will be the longevity of his team. 
President Napolitano wants to avoid early elections because Italy must place by April 2012 for 200 billion euros of government bonds. 
A Russian scientist helped the Iranian nuclear program 
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran to develop a usable detonator with a nuclear weapon, said Monday, an American NGO specialising in nuclear risk. 
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on the recent report by the International Agency for Atomic Security (IAEA) and other documents from the UN agency to identify the researcher. 
The IAEA reported last week its "serious concerns" about a "possible military dimension" of the Iranian nuclear program. 
According to ISIS largely from documents of the IAEA, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, had worked for three decades from the 1960s in a Soviet military nuclear center at Chelyabinsk (Urals), and would have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion. 
In 1989 or 1991, he would have left the centre to establish a company producing "nano diamonds" in Kiev. 
The economic difficulties of his company would have led to contact the Embassy of Iran in Ukraine in 1995. 
He would then cooperated in the Iranian programme in 1996 to 2002, before his return to Russia. 
In its latest report, the IAEA refers to "strong indications that the development by Iran" of a nuclear detonation system "has been helped by the work of a foreign expert, who not only knew this technique, but who, as a Member State has informed the Agency, has worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear programme in his country of origin." 
Anti-Muslim crimes and offences have increased by 50% 
The crimes and offences against Muslims have increased by almost 50% from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, other religious and racial violence have declined slightly or little progress, according to FBI statistics released Monday. 
According to these figures, the total number of violence perpetrated against Muslims rose from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49% increase, against an increase of 13% of violence against Catholics, a decrease of 4% of offences against Jews and an increase of 14% of crimes and offences anti-religious. 
The total number of "hate crimes" rose marginally to 6,628 cases, 47.3% motivated by differences of race and 20% by differences of religion, according to the FBI. 
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offences increase again," said Human Rights First, "the increase in antimusulmanes violence is particularly significant," said in a statement. 
"Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be regarded as a serious violation of human rights," said one of the leaders of the organization, Paul Legendre. 
"The US government can and must do more to tackle these abuses," he said, arguing that it could pass through improved police reports on "hate crimes." 
The "hate crime" in the US federal law is a legacy of the era of the struggle for civil rights. 
This legislation had been adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, colour, religion, origin and now sex. 
Twitter is changing its platform and is more akin to Facebook 
The site of micro blogging Twitter introduced Monday changes in the presentation of its platform to allow its users to observe the activity of those they follow, which is like a little more than Facebook. 
A new "activity" and another "name" to follow more legibly, direct the activity of other "Twittos," which follows the messages ("tweets") and those who will follow. 
This allows us to know if they follow messages, if they subscribe to new accounts, if they have favourite messages, etc. 
This new form of Twitter has been tested "on a small percentage of users in August" before being distributed to the entire network Monday, told the AFP spokesman for Twitter, Carolyn Penner. 
Twitter, which was known for its functioning little instinctive, with somewhat esoteric terms (RT to broadcast a message from someone else, #followfriday to recommend another user) happiness insiders, opens to a wider audience with a more comparable to those of mainstream networks Facebook and Google +. 
On the network, users discussed "tweets" decided on the value of this innovation. 
"It is unnecessary, intrusive, and it is too similar to Facebook," wrote. 
"Functionality will help me to better follow certain elements of my Twitter stream," was sent. 
Austria 
Registration of a fiscal "golden rule" in the constitution 
The government of Social Democrat/Christian Democrat ruling coalition in Austria decided Tuesday to enshrine in the constitution a fiscal "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible deterioration in the credit rating agencies of the sovereign rating of Austria (triple A). 
It is the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann announced this decision at the end of a council of ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the criterion of 60% maximum set by the Maastricht Treaty, but far below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain. 
"If the solvency of Austria was lowered one notch from AAA to AA +, we should pay three billion euros of interest every year," argued Christian Democrat Vice-Chancellor and Minister of Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger. 
Austria following a request from the summit in Brussels of the member countries of the eurozone on 26 October: the heads of state and government had called for the registration by the end of 2012 for the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or a law of equal value. 
The system adopted by the Austrian government is moving closer to the "German model," Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule." 
By 2017, the public deficit will decrease each year from 0.75% of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and, starting in 2017, the public deficit of the federal state should not exceed each year 0.35% of GDP, while the states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets. 
The goal is to move to 2020/21 public debt below the 60% criteria set by the Maastricht Treaty. 
Strong yen 
Noda threat of a new intervention in the foreign exchange market 
The Japanese prime minister, Yoshihiko Noda, warned Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would once again on the foreign exchange market if the yen were to continue to rise. 
"We will act as we have done the last time if we see an excessive volatility" in the exchange rate of the yen, " said Mr. Noda in the Senate. 
On Tuesday, the yen was near historic levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on 31 October. 
That day, Tokyo has massively sold yen against the dollar in order to lower the value of the Japanese currency that had just set a new record since 1945 against the greenback. 
But the yen has steadily risen since then, boosted by purchases of investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic downturn and debt crisis in Europe. 
The dollar rose Tuesday in 77 yen and the euro fell below the symbolic level of 105 yen, near levels that have triggered the latest intervention. 
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar stood at around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen. 
The outbreak of the Japanese currency hurts exports of the archipelago because it says the cost of products made in Japan and reduces the value of income from abroad by Japanese firms, when they convert them into national currency. 
"Japan struggle to rebuild" since the earthquake and tsunami of 11 March that devastated the region in the Tohoku (northeast), said Mr. Noda who fear that the rise of the yen does not kill in the bud the fragile recovery. 
The third world economic power has returned to growth in the third quarter of 1.5% compared to the previous quarter - for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and household consumption leaded by the disaster. 
But the Prime Minister has ruled that the high yen does not reflect "the economic fundamentals of Japan." 
The Minister of Finance, Jun Azumi, has called on the Bank of Japan (BOJ), which opened Tuesday a two-day meeting of its board of monetary policy, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen. 
But the deputy governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BOJ had already taken "appropriate measures," suggesting that no monetary flexibility was to wait until Wednesday. 
At its last meeting in late October, the Institute of emissions increased by 5,000 billion yen (47 billion euros) its purchases of Treasuries, increasing to 55,000 billion yen (519 billion euros) the ceiling amounts that it devotes to purchases of various financial securities to flood the market with liquidity. 
