Energy policy: 
The facts must outweigh the dogmas 
If there is an issue that we cannot treat from short-term considerations or emotion, it is the energy policy. 
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and the competitiveness of businesses. 
It is healthy that a rendezvous is the opportunity to reflect on such issues and nuclear power. 
The debate will be successful only if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options. 
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data. 
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, the demographic changes will result in a doubling of electricity by 2050, unless depriving a huge part of the world population of a vital element. 
At the same time, it will be necessary to overcome the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases to combat climate change, a subject disappeared from the environmental debate. 
The accident in Fukushima does none of these parameters. 
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power. 
This is the case of Belgium, which makes her the need to be able to find an alternative source able to substitute or Switzerland, which is just not built that last generation plants. 
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, for example, are pursuing their projects with determination. 
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park by resuming the construction of a plant suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island. 
If the German model, focused on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality frustrates the speech. 
The choice of Berlin will translate into a rise in the price of electricity, energy dependence aggravated by the increasing reliance on imported gas, particularly from Russia, a surge of CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas-fired power plants and coal. 
In a few months, all of these unfortunate effects are already being felt. 
The case of Denmark is to ponder. 
European champion of the wind, which derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of wind; its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average. 
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an invoice 40% more electricity to French households. 
While in a globalized economy, the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies have the cheapest electricity in Europe. 
Thus, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would create a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make false declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and defending the purchasing power. 
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially given that they are not opposed in principle to this energy, polls show. 
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has helped to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 jobs. 
A strong exporter, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs on international markets and makes them very job-creating non-transferable. 
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing as shrinking 6 billion euros of French exports nuclear equipment and services. 
What would a PRT designed to operate 60 years ago when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed? 
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no source of production d " miracle power, nor that there is evil. 
The development by Areva of low emitters of CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions, illustrates the complementarity of sources of energy. 
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of security is an absolute imperative. 
We have a security authority in France that has a transparent and strict control over the existing plants on the site of Flamanville site. 
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same security obsession. 
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents. 
One, Three Mile Island, intervened in normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences. 
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and human unforgivable mistakes have caused the tragedy. 
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people. 
The nuclear industry will draw the lessons from this accident, as it did for the previous two. 
Result of this approach and cooperation between security authorities, operators and the French and German manufacturers, the PRT has a design making it able to resist such phenomena. 
While it is regarded by all electricians who want to build a power station, halting its construction to Flamanville site would be a magnificent gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF leaving them free to seize leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power. 
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan tactics dominate a debate as crucial to the economic, social and financial situation of our country. 
Immigration is a burden or a chance for the economy? 
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from different angles - police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed "country of human rights" of France. 
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of 23 May) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talent, builders and restaurant servers." 
But it is only rarely analysed in economic terms. 
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between left and right. 
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers," and left by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990. 
The only difference, the degree of generosity 
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left and right. 
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and the French company. 
The only difference is the degree of generosity that daignera towards immigrants. 
In his programme, François Hollande confined to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem." 
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem may be electorally profitable, but it is economically very expensive. 
As the recall economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (of People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants. 
Restricting immigration anemic growth and damaging employment. 
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they can substitute for domestic workers, especially low-skilled, to exert downward pressure on their wages. 
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for domestic workers, most of the trades in sectors lack of employment. 
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training is not the supply of jobs. 
A positive effect on wages 
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country that is experiencing a shortage of anaesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on wages and employment. 
Giovanni Peri has calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term. 
Without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of immigrants naturalized American Nobel Prize; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants). 
Migrants are also contributors of social systems, on average 1% of the total budget in European countries. 
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 years will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenses) from 150,000 to public budgets on average over the whole of his life. 
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the mandate, pick up the missing points of growth "with teeth." 
The teeth used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect. 
Europe has invented democracy, is to think European democracy 
Democracy is a precious commodity; it is also a very fragile. 
The European continent should be remembered for having invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, has seen throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece. 
Some were able to believe that it would be enough to ensure that democracy triomphât definitively from its enemies, to exercise the vote, and the most direct way. 
We know, since Napoleon "Petit," that it was an ease of thought. 
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and may even be "instrument of oppression" as once the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot. 
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice. 
The crisis in Europe that we live in is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and start a crisis of politics and democracy. 
The palinodie of the vrai-faux Greek referendum will be held in this regard revealing double value: the need for a powerful return of politics, but also the disturbing sense of impossibility, for its incongruity. 
This ambivalence must be thought to be outdated. 
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle today were displaced, and that, for many of them, the Republican soldiers are no longer in the right direction. 
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, held as necessities and disorganised. 
A blank cheque to the European absolute monarch or a leap to feet in the vacuum of the nationalist downturn: what choice for the citizen! 
No, we do not want cleavers but an exercise, right, calm and continuous, choice and democracy, this time at the European level. 
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we cannot stop the list - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe. 
It is Europe as a whole conform to the dictates of the markets and credit rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity. 
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated on the international stage. 
It is concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole who slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations. 
The urgency is to restore the popular sovereignty the piloting of the European project. 
Because it is that the Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free markets and prepare for the future by investing. 
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without a full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster. 
Having long fought this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is calling for the European economic government. 
Either. 
But the thinking without a stronger democratic and political integration, and seen as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse. 
We need to take a new stage of European construction. 
For the Republic in France, it took "to" Republicans. 
The Revolution in interest could not be enough. 
This lesson remains valid. 
We must build a Europe more integrated economically. 
This can be done only by building a more democratic Europe on the political front, a genuine European popular sovereignty. 
In Europe, are Europeans. 
Smart cards "without contact" spreading 
The World Fair smartcard opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in an optimistic climate. 
The year 2011 should be completed on an increase of 11% of global sales of smart cards (bank card, phone SIM card...), more than 6 billion units, according to the Eurosmart firm. 
The most promising segment is the contactless technology that makes it possible to pay transit or to settle its purchases by simply approaching the map of a reader. 
This year, 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold around the world, from 320 million a year earlier. 
Their share should increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent nearly 10% of the global market for smart card ($6.925 million cards). 
Long lagging behind in the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground for payment without contact. 
Some 26 million bank Visa are already equipped with this functionality and 75,000 payment terminals accept. 
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed. 
But mass merchandisers make strides. 
Carrefour issued this year and 2.5 million cards Pass MasterCard without contact. 
To move to a higher level, it is now that banks on their clients. 
"Two big French pledged to disseminate future systematically to their customers cards equipped to contact," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director General Visa Europe France. 
Banks test payment by mobile 
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment for the future: the mobile phone. 
Few devices are now equipped with the technology NFC (Near Field Communication) needed to carry out transactions. 
"They have fallen behind." 
"But they should finally see a real boom next year." 
"We rely on the sale of 80 to 120 million units in 2012 in the world," said Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart. 
But the banks are taking the lead. 
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test from December to June at Caen. 
The iPhone of some 200 customers and staff will be equipped with a holster authorizing the payment without contact. 
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille. 
And the General Society, too, said yesterday to prepare for the marketing of an offer to allow its customers to pay without contact with their mobile. 
Western Sahara in Nigeria, the terrorist front extends 
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the sect Boko Haram. 
Long suspected links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram is confirmed. 
On Sunday, the Algerian Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, has even said that Algiers has now "acquired certainty." 
"The way in which the two organisations operate and the reports of the intelligence services show that there is good cooperation," he said without more detail. 
Paris seems to make a similar analysis. 
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger in January would have uncovered bridges. 
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their abductors during an operation launched by the French special forces. 
In the rubble of the intervention, the French and Nigerian investigators were to return several telephone chips belonging to terrorists. 
Terrorist axis 
The analysis of the calls directed towards several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria. 
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigérien who has travelled extensively in Maiduguri, a city in the north of Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram and the other to a man who is close to Aqmi and the sect. 
"It is a step forward, but we should probably expect more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram." 
"But it is possible." 
"It has been known for years that the sect enjoys financial support and foreign intellectuals and that it is increasingly active," probably Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher. 
In recent months these "support" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its methods, which include the use of suicide bombers or explosives increasingly complex and even bill than those used by Aqmi. 
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore lobbied Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram. 
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illuminated little interest. 
A rapid success 
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means haoussa "Western education is a sin" - calls for the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria. 
In this poor region, the association is undergoing a rapid success. 
It is politicizing and requires a strict observance of Sharia law while its militants committed the fight against the central government impious. 
These are first churches, bars, administrations. 
In 2009, the militants of Boko Haram are particularly active, multiplying attacks against police stations. 
The Abuja reaction is, as usual, without nuances. 
The army is the city, there are 800 deaths. 
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, was killed in prison. 
So the sect will be radicalized and leave its northern fiefdoms. 
Last Christmas, it claims an attack that 80 people were killed in Jos, then another in Abuja. 
In June, it is still in Abuja that Boko Haram takes the secure headquarters of the police during an attack suicide, his first. 
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target. 
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that is operating from Mauritania to Somalia from Nigeria worried now all security specialists. 
While Aqmi has invested Mali and Niger, that the Somalis Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat to the heart of the continent. 
Last week, during an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and is willing to share all the information." 
The world according to Republican candidates for the presidency 
On China, Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry vie for superficiality and ignorance. 
America weakened by the crisis can manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas? 
To listen to the Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe. 
