"If I am elected, I will leave Iran, he fanfaronné." 
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb." 
He has also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing in its obligations to the partner. 
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, second best candidate, has an embarrassing lack of records. 
Recently, he called to counter the Chinese military threat because Beijing "is trying to develop a nuclear capability" - apparently ignoring the fact that China holds the military atom since 1964. 
The Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, is ready to engage the US army in Mexico against the drug cartels. 
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, prohibited by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and the candidate Michele Bachmann. 
It is far from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy. 
Opponents of the current president argued that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he has won the Cold War. 
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine in terms of counterterrorism. 
They rightly stress the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, the over-hasty departure "boys" in Iraq, on his procrastination in Libya, hugging a small label. 
But the attack is not so easy. 
The population sees positive stock of Obama's national security, which has eliminated Bin Laden. 
In Iraq, it is wary of military interventions that lead to the stalemate. 
And, on the grounds that there is a need to economically rebuild America to revive its leadership, Obama strikes fairer. 
The Nord Stream, new ntrée of Russian gas in Europe 
The Nord Stream gas pipeline directly linking Western Europe to Russia at the bottom of the Baltic Sea, came into service. 
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households. 
Gazprom, the giant Russian gas, has sought to celebrate the event. 
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government participated, last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and buffet at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline linking directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany. 
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, Prime Minister of France François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the wheel of the valve commander of Russian gas in the European-Western network. 
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 kilometers linking the St Petersburg region in the Land of Mecklenburg. 
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of the entire French consumption. 
And mention the possibility of building a third on the same route. 
For Gazprom, the completion of this huge project victory. 
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries. 
The Nord Stream will indeed be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine). 
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to shut down access to Western European markets. 
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939. 
That is to say if the issue is politically sensitive. 
Western Europe, with its support for the Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies. 
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between East and West Europeans. 
Russia has been able, in five years ago, making his vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are in decline. 
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon launching this pipeline, demonstrating how the major gas contracts are also political and economic. 
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, in numbers to Lubmin, to the point of arrival of gas. 
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat. 
The submarine tube is steel gainé concrete in order to protect against ship anchors. 
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average. 
To build, it was necessary to avoid mines from the Second World War. 
"One hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream. 
It has also taken more measures to protect flora and fauna. 
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing stops along its entire length: neither valve, nor station maintenance. 
A monitoring platform was planned off Sweden, but the project was abandoned when the Swedes were reluctant to see a society of Russian state permanently off their coasts. 
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," said Jens Müller. 
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air. 
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned welds for a leak every 100,000 years. 
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a robot submarine, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as a device that circulates inside the pipeline. 
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced in the tube, a metre in diameter, and it is driven by the gas. 
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters per second, it delivers accurate information on the possible distortions of the metal. 
The pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without having to undergo the slightest repair. 
The flow of gas is simply guaranteed by the pressure. 
It is 200 bars at the outset, and 100 on arrival. 
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project. 
The leader is Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares. 
Joined the German E. ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez (9% each). 
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline. 
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable. 
Gazprom was then leased to the company for 20 years, the entire gas transport capacity. 
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," said Jens Müller. 
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans. 
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes. 
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million. 
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk. 
The pipeline is emerging from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted pine. 
Valves, high of 4.5 metres, form the exit door of the gas. 
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and characteristics of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German pipelines. 
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes. 
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million. 
Moleskine, a brand notebook. 
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing. 
He has a whiff of adventures, hours to write in the light of a candle. 
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular coverage, its elastic, leaves a white broken, as dated by the time. 
However, the book Moleskine as we know today was born... in 1997. 
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a book of design but distinguished notes. 
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product. 
The book is based on an old technique of production, the mole skin (skin), which refers to a cotton varnish used to cover seats for example. 
This type of book was very popular among writers and travellers. 
"Moleskine has given buzz-words an old and forgotten, who was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, now the head of the mark in Modo Modo. 
The success is there. 
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins. 
It is far from the confidential production of the early years, where only 3,000 books were designed. 
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exported in 70 countries, from France to the United States. 
Difficult to establish a profile of the buyer, because the rating attracts both the businessman that students and professionals. 
The image of Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated. 
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, almost 100 today and has since 2008 two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York. 
It distributes its books in bookstores, the FNACs small shops in downtown and was able to impose its identity. 
"We have followed the air time and this new writing, despite the rise of Email," said Maria Sebregondi. 
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists put their own book. 
In August, it has also launched a leopard coverage at the Festival of the Locarno film. 
Taking advantage of its success and cultural Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer bags... the mark is on a range of formats. 
A success that has made envious: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine. 
Why the unemployment rate for workers with disabilities remain so high? 
About 19% of people with disabilities are in search of a job. 
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today. 
Despite a proactive policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still two times higher than the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole of the population. 
Discouraging? 
"No, says Eric Jacques-Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people." 
"The progress made over the past 15 years are considerable." 
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher." 
"There is still a lot to do." 
It must be said that for the disabled unemployed, the obstacles remain before access to employment. 
They are older: 37% more than 50 years (17% on average). 
They have a low level of qualification: 80% did not and 2.3 million students in higher education, 10,000 are disabled. 
Finally, the long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average. 
In short, as many criteria more complicated the return to employment, and who "are the crux of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies to recruit disabled workers. 
This is the brakes. 
It remains unspoken, attitudes are changing, of course, but too slowly. 
A study conducted in April by the IMS association - Initiate Precinct indicated that managers interviewed "a low level of knowledge of disability," with a "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities." 
The result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of employment of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987. 
The latest figures, dating from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%. 
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre White, Director General of AGEFIPH's, the body responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with the law. 
The evidence: the number of establishments "taxed," just as the amounts paid, declined between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and 606 to 480 million euros). 
"The law of 2005, which increased contributions, has created a strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc. 
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups." 
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments from 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees. 
Hazard: "Happiness" 
Before facing the Azzurri on Tuesday evening (8.45pm) Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens have not hidden the pleasure afforded this match. 
We will not go so far as to write that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic. 
Sitting side by side on the podium in the auditorium of the Stade de France, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard did indeed make peace. 
Five months after the mood gesture of his attack against Turkey, the Belgian breeder has only praise. 
"I am very happy to Eden, its progress and the fact that he is Belgian." 
"I want to move forward," says Lillois. 
As for the contrastre between his club benefits and selection, "it's a whole, has justified." 
"In Lille, I am the entire year, which is not the case with Belgium." 
"It is important that I take my brands." 
Against Romania Friday night for the game against France, Hazard comes at Saint-Denis to finally "shine." 
Without forgetting, however, the notion of "fun." 
The Blues, he has promoted since the age of 7 years and victorious campaigns in 1998 and 2000. 
"I have always been bear," he said. 
Inevitably, this helps to strengthen the "special character" of this meeting. 
Even in the face, "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil Rami)," said he. 
"It was earlier." 
"Being able to play against them, it is only happiness!" 
