"You are going to report in the coming matches." against France. 
Portugal very confident 
Portugal Paulo Bento begins with a lot of optimistic his return to Bosnia (10pm), Tuesday in Lisbon. 
The move, the two teams had lacked realism. 
"At the end of the 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country." 
Paulo Bento, in Poland and Ukraine. 
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, which is the joysticks since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012. 
Portugal is only 90 minutes of happiness. 
But there is a game to play, and an opponent, Bosnia, to counter. 
In view of the game to go (0 - 0) Friday in the hell of Zenica, it is clear that the games are not made. 
Portugal has dominated the party for more than an hour, of course, but it has been unable to mark this precious goal, which would have relieved. 
"It is a good result, which entails a certain risk because we have not marked" 
But at home, in their luminous Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced, before an audience that should be here too, even if the party is obviously "very tight," as a lucid but optimistic Bento. 
"We expect a very tight match, but we are quite convinced that they can take the upper hand," said the Portuguese coach for 42 years. 
"We continue to have 50% chance of being at the Euro 2012," has put the successor to Carlos Queiroz. 
No one reported Friday in Bosnia obliges the Portuguese to score and win. 
It may be enough for the Bosnians, who also need to mark. 
"It is a good result, which entails a certain risk because we have not left outside," Bento regrets. 
"We are going to play against a team that has a lot of technical qualities and has players with a lot of individual qualities," he added. 
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will intend to put maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "not give them time to reflect." 
A good idea to be realistic, this time. 
